<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Criticizes Israeli Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat on Tuesday lashed out at Israel's
settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is continuing to build settlements in
the occupied Palestinian territories, Arafat said upon arrival at
Cairo for a short visit.
</P>
<P>
The latest was the building of 1,084 housing units around
Bethlehem, Egypt's Middle East News Agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader warned that the Israeli settlement
policy will jeopardize the ongoing negotiations for a final peace
agreement between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The signed peace deals between the two sides oblige Israel to
halt its settlement activities in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
The future of the Jewish settlements will be decided in the final
status talks. But Israel has so far failed to honor the accords.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision came at a time when Muslims and Christians
are planning to celebrate the new millennium in the West Bank
town, Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's move indicates that "it wanted to impede the planned
celebrations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat added that Israel also continues to build settlements in
Jerusalem, describing the activity as an attempt to judaize the
holy city.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want the traditional Arab East Jerusalem as
the capital of their future independent state. But Israel claims
that Jerusalem is its "undivided and eternal capital." The final
status talks also include this thorny issue.
</P>
<P>
Arafat frequently visits Egypt to consult with President Hosni
Mubarak and seek his advice. Egypt, the first Arab country to sign
a peace treaty with Israel, plays an active role in mediating the
Arab-Israeli peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
