<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Electronic Signature Directive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
telecommunications ministers adopted Tuesday a new legal framework
guaranteeing EU-wide recognition of electronic signatures.
</P>
<P>
The Electronic Signature Directive was cleared during an one-
day meeting of EU Council of ministers. The European Commission,
the EU's executive branch, said this is the first example of its "
flexible and integrated" efforts towards developing a European
framework for the progress of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
EU's 15 member states now have 18 months to implement the law
which is expected to enhance Internet security and help Europe
make good the e-commerce gap between the regional bloc and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
In the past, only hand-written signatures have been legally
valid but this legislation extends that recognition to electronic
signatures and applies the Internet market principles of free
movement of services and home country control to e-commerce, the
European Commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"This framework provides the security that the market for
online transactions demands and strengthens the EU's position in
the face of international competition in this new global market,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
Electronic signatures allow someone receiving data over
electronic networks, via the Internet for example, to determine
the origin of the data and to check that the data had not been
altered.
</P>
<P>
The directive is not designed to regulate everything in detail
but defines the requirements for electronic signature certificates
and certification services so as to ensure minimum levels of
security and allow their free movement throughout the Internet
market, the EU executive said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
