<HEADLINE> China Ready to Work Together with Other Asian Countries: Zhu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singapore, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
said here Tuesday that China stands ready to continue to work
together with other Asian countries and safeguard the healthy
atmosphere and momentum of dialogue and cooperation with a view to
maintaining peace, stability and prosperity in the region in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the statement while delivering a speech at the
"Singapore Lecture," which is the 17th of a series hosted by
Singapore's Institute of Southeast Asian Studies and designed to
provide an opportunity for distinguished statesmen and leaders to
reach a wider audience in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said China, as one of the initiators of the Five Principles
of Peaceful Co-existence, has developed ties of
good-neighborliness and friendship with other Asian countries
strictly according to the principles of mutual respect, treating
each other as equals, seeking common ground while shelving
differences and conducting mutually-beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The ever-growing ties between China and other Asian countries
have shown that as long as these principles are upheld, all
countries in Asia can live together in peace and harmony despite
differences in the size, historical background, social system,
level of development, cultural tradition and value, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He said good-neighborliness, friendship and peace represent the
common interests and needs of China and ASEAN countries, adding
that the rejuvenation of China's economy cannot be achieved
without the development of Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said the government and people of China stands ready to work
together with other Asian countries and people in the following
aspects:
</P>
<P>
-- To continue to develop the partnership of
good-neighborliness and mutual trust between China and other Asian
nations in line with the purposes of the Joint Statement issued by
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and leaders of ASEAN nations in 1997
and the documents governing the cross-century development of
bilateral relations signed between China and some Asian countries
and on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence;
</P>
<P>
-- To pay close attention to the trend of economic
globalization and respond to it in an active and prudent manner by
choosing a development road suited to itself and proceeding from
its specific national conditions;
</P>
<P>
-- To endeavor to improve the hi-tech level and increase the
ability for technical innovation by giving top priority to
accelerating scientific and technological progress and innovation
in the development strategy and laying emphasis on the fundamental
role of education and actively recruiting professionals with
innovation power;
</P>
<P>
-- To establish a full-fledged and sound financial system that
is efficient and reliable so as to eliminate the latent dangers
that might lead to a financial crisis, and to continue to
intensify the financial reform;
</P>
<P>
-- To give play to the proper role of the market and the
government with a view to realizing economic reinvigoration so as
to increase economic vitality and efficiency and strengthen macro
control of the national economy;
</P>
<P>
-- To continue to tap the potentials for mutually beneficial
cooperation between China and ASEAN countries in areas such as
trade, investment, science and technology, agriculture, tourism,
machinery and electronics, telecommunications, medicine,
environmental protection and human resources development.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu said China hopes to establish contacts with the
ASEAN Free Trade Area and the ASEAN Investment Area and is ready
to provide funding support to the development of the Mekong River
basin area.
</P>
<P>
He also reaffirmed that China welcomes ASEAN entrepreneurs to
China for economic, trading and investment activities, and in
particular, their participation in the all-out development
strategy of China's western region and will continue to encourage
and support Chinese enterprises to invest and set up factories in
ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also stressed that China faithfully observes the political
consensus reached with ASEAN , ready to continue to safeguard the
healthy atmosphere and momentum of dialogue and cooperation and
properly address differences and disputes through friendly
consultations on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
Zhu is the first Chinese leader to deliver a speech at the
"Singapore Lecture," and he briefed the international forum on the
developments in China and put forth his views on the development
prospects for China and Asia. He was given a standing ovation when
he was stepping onto the podium.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong chaired the
lecture which was attended by more than 1,200 people, including
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, government ministers,
well-known business leaders and foreign ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu's speech was frequently punctuated with applause
and his humorous remarks aroused bursts of laughter from his
audience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
