<HEADLINE> 21st Century Offers Asia Chances, Challenges: China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 30 (Xinhua) -- China Tuesday called on
Asian nations to seize opportunities and cope with challenges as
they march toward the next century.
</P>
<P>
"There will be both unprecedented opportunities and a myriad of
severe challenges, foreseeable or unforeseeable, in the next
century," said Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji here in a policy speech
delivered at the 17th Singapore Lecture.
</P>
<P>
For Asian countries, they need to open arms to embrace and
grasp those opportunities and to learn to meet challenges, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Only by doing so, he said, will Asia be able to "obtain a
position of strength in the vicissitudes and intense competition
in the new century," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said China is ready to work with other Asian countries in
various aspects to maintain peace and prosperity in Asia in the
new century.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Lecture is designed to provide an opportunity for
distinguished statesmen and leaders to reach a wider audience in
Singapore, according to a brochure sent out by the Institute of
Southeast Asian Studies, the host of the Lecture.
</P>
<P>
Zhu's audience included Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong,
Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong, government ministers and
senior officials from both public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Zhu arrived in Singapore on Monday for a three-day official
visit. He will leave for Vietnam on Wednesday, the last stop of
his four-nation Southeast Asian tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
