<HEADLINE> Arabs Calls for Iranian Steps in Solving Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League on Tuesday urged
Iran to take steps to resolve the dispute with the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) over three Gulf islands.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to mark what the Arab League said the 28-year
occupation of the islands by Iran, the pan-Arab organization
demanded the Iranian government "take functional steps that will
translate its declared good intentions" over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Iran sent troops to the islands of Greater Tunb, Less Tunb and
Abu Musa after British withdrawal in 1971. The UAE also claims
sovereignty over the islands near the strategic Straits of
Hormuz. But the two countries have said they are ready to solve
the dispute through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged Iran to respond to UAE's initiative to
solve the problem through international arbitration, a way the
league said is in line with good neighborliness, mutual interests
and international laws.
</P>
<P>
Iran, however, prefers direct negotiations with the UAE.
</P>
<P>
A peaceful solution to the dispute will have a positive impact
on the security and stability in the strategically important Gulf
region, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The league said in the statement that it made the call out of
keenness on improving the Arab-Iranian relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
