<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Musharraf Rules out Putting Kashmir on Back Burner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Chief Executive
General Pervaiz Musharraf has ruled out the possibility of putting
the Kashmir issue on the back burner and said it was the main
impediment in the improvement of relations between Pakistan and
India.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe in distorting views for the sake of diplomacy.
Kashmir is the core issue. Now if anyone thinks it is not, I
really don't know how to convince them otherwise," he said in an
interview with the Times Asia magazine.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question regarding the "new approach" for
improvement of relations with India, Musharraf said: "If you mean
to put Kashmir aside, how can you do that?"
</P>
<P>
"We are killing each other on the Line of Control. People are
dying in Kashmir and I go happy and smiling and grinning and meet
all the Indian leaders? We are talking something and thinking
something else in our hearts. So are they," he said. "I'm not like
that. I can't do that. If there is some tension in my heart, it is
on my face. I'm not a believer in these things."
</P>
<P>
On the Kargil conflict this summer, the chief executive said:
"I was chief of the army staff, so I take full responsibility for
whatever my army does or does not do."
</P>
<P>
However, he said the Kargil issue has to be seen in the total
perspective of Kashmir and such actions and far-reaching decisions
were not taken by one man alone. "Everyone was on board, including
the (deposed) prime minister who was very much aware of the whole
package."
</P>
<P>
"As far as my attitude toward India is concerned, I've been
very realistic," he said. "We have fought wars over Kashmir and
every day there is an exchange of fire along the Line of Control.
I surely believe there has to be peace in the region and we have
to resolve all our issues with India."
</P>
<P>
"That is the only way this region can progress economically.
It's the poorest region in the world. But can we do anything
without progress on Kashmir? No, we can't, it's just not
realistic," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Kashmir has to be addressed "because this is the issue
that is hampering any kind of agreement between the two
countries."
</P>
<P>
He said it would be very disappointing if U.S. President Bill
Clinton would bypass Pakistan on his planned South Asia visit next
year. "I feel that by coming here, the president of the United
States will have a positive impact. His visit will affect the
whole region. Sidelining Pakistan would be counter-productive.
There would be a gap in his understanding. The people of Pakistan
would be terribly disappointed." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
