<HEADLINE> Quebec Court Rules on Use of Chinese Language in Chinese Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The Quebec Superior court has
ruled the Chinese language can be a job requirement for nurses at
the Montreal Chinese Hospital, the local newspaper Gazette
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under a ruling made on November 18 by Justice Irving Halperin,
the hospital could demand a knowledge of Chinese as a job
requirement for nurses.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that the hospital not only has the right but the
duty to defend its own best interests, with a goal toward
protecting its patients' welfare and protecting their rights,"
wrote Halperin.
</P>
<P>
About 63 percent of patients at the Montreal Chinese Hospital
are unilingual Chinese, who say, "the staff are very nice, but
they don't always understand them (the patients)."
</P>
<P>
In one case, the Montreal-based Gazette reported, May Poon's
elderly mother wanted to go to the toilet, but nobody understood
what she was saying.
</P>
<P>
Poon is one of several Chinese Montrealers who feel that more
staff at the hospital should speak either the Cantonese or
Toisanese dialects, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
