<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Blasts Turkish PM's Statement on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday criticized the
statement made by Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit concerning
the neighboring country's stance on Cyprus and the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that Turkey's position was undermining its
own European prospects.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was not being asked to make any concessions but it was
being asked to respect international law and international
treaties, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that Athens would set out its
position on the issue of Turkey's European Union (EU) candidate
status at the December Helsinki summit on the basis of
developments expected during the discussion on this issue.
</P>
<P>
For decades, Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at
odds over their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits and the continental shelf in the Aegean Sea, and the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Athens has said that it is now ready to support Ankara's EU
accession due to the recent improvement in the relations between
the two neighbors, but it is also awaiting the goodwill gestures
from Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit reportedly said Monday that Turkey did not intend to
make concessions neither on Cyprus nor the Aegea Sea.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that Athens will possibly veto Turkey's
EU candidacy if the substance of its demands is not met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
