<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Leaders Meet for Anti-govt Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The chiefs of four opposition
parties in Bangladesh met for the first time here Tuesday to work
out strategies to intensify their on-going movement to unseat the
government.
</P>
<P>
During the much talked about meeting, the four leaders decided
to further consolidate the unity of the opposition alliance and
intensify their movement to compel the government of Sheikh Hasina
to step down.
</P>
<P>
"A patriotic government will have to be formed on the basis of
the broad-based unity of the people to face the challenges of the
new century," said a Joint Declaration signed by Khaleda zia of
the Bangladesh Nationalist party, Ershad of Jatiya Party, Golam
Azam of Jamaat-e-Islami and Azizul Huq of Islami Oikhy Jote
(Islamic Solidarity Front).
</P>
<P>
The Joint Declaration highlighted politicization by the
government, its failure to meet election pledges, "anti-people and
anti-national" Ganges Water Sharing Treaty signed with India and
deterioration of law and order.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called on people across the country to form
committees focused on forcing the government to resign and hand
over the power to a caretaker government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
