<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Chief Calls for Health-Related New Global Trading System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The head of the World Health
Organization (WHO) has called on trade ministers and negotiators
to strive for an international trade system that promotes human
progress for all.
</P>
<P>
In a statement made public here Tuesday when representatives
from 135 members of the World Trade Organization (WTO) began their
four-day conference in Seattle, WHO Director-General Gro Harlem
Brundtland said that those in charge of global trade must place at
the core of their attention the striking market failure that one
third of the world population still lack access to essential drugs.
</P>
<P>
In the poorest parts of Africa and Asia, the WHO chief noted,
over 50 percent of the population are deprived of access to the
essential drugs. "This is simply not acceptable," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The last WTO round provided the Agreement on Trade Related
Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPS). It provides scope
for the protection of public health," she recalled. "WHO member
states have been urged to explore and review their options under
international agreements, including trade agreements, to safeguard
access to essential drugs."
</P>
<P>
Brundtland said that WHO would monitor the implementation of
the TRIPS agreement and advise countries on policies which will
help protect and enhance their public health policies.
</P>
<P>
She urged the governments, which are both WTO and WHO members,
"to honor their commitments to make health central to human
development".
</P>
<P>
"Issues such as removal of trade barriers, standards for food
safety, and access to drugs are key ingredients for measuring
progress in health and development," she stressed. "Health is not
a side-effect of trade, it is a yardstick to monitor human
progress." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
