<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Problems Between Turkey, Greece Should be Resolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem said on Tuesday that problems between Turkey and
Greece should be resolved through "peaceful methods."
</P>
<P>
Cem made the remarks in a written statement concerning the
incoming European Union (EU) summit in Helsinki, Finland, which
will discuss if to give Turkey candidacy for EU membership, the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that "Turkey does not have any territorial ambitions
from Greece. It is possible for the two neighboring and allied
countries to change the Aegean Sea into a sea of friendship and
peace by acceptable means. This should be the common target of the
two countries."
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both NATO members, have been locked in
disputes for decades over territorial waters, air space limits,
delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean Sea, and the
Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
On Turkey's application for entry into the EU, Cem said in the
statement that progress in Turkey's full EU membership would make
a considerable contribution to the security in the region where
Turkey is located.
</P>
<P>
But he pointed out that the Cyprus issue and the relations
between Turkey and EU are two separate issues.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is absolutely opposed to evaluation of the relations
with the EU within the context of Cyprus," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the land
in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. Turkey and Greece supported
their own ethnic side.
</P>
<P>
Problems including Turkey-Greece relations have affected
Turkey's efforts to join EU which Turkey has applied for since
1987. But Cem emphasized that inclusion of Turkey into EU is a
prior target of Turkey but not an obsession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
