<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriots Visit Monastery in Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,766 Greek
Cypriots Tuesday went to the Turkish Cypriots-controlled northern
part of Cyprus to visit the monastery of Saint Apostolos Andreas,
in the eastern tip of the island.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by U.N. peacekeepers, clutching candles in their
hands, they crossed into the northern Cyprus to pray at the
monastery on the occasion of the saint's day. The journey to the
monastery by bus took about three hours.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Before 1974, thousands of pilgrims visited the monastery on
the saint's day.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, Greek Cypriots paid several visits
to the northern Turkish Cypriot area on special religious days,
such as Easter Sunday or Assumption day.
</P>
<P>
Similar trips were also arranged for Turkish Cypriots over
the past few years to places of worship in the
southern area, which is controlled by the Cyprus government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian FM Blasts West Over Chechnya, Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov on Tuesday blasted the West for exerting pressure on Russia
over Chechnya and conniving with genocide against Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said Western countries were trying to force Russia out of
the Caucasus and the Caspian region.
</P>
<P>
Moscow "will resolutely resist" such attempts, Ivanov told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
"An evident battle for spheres of influence is underway in the
Caspian region and the Caucasus," the minister said. "Individual
states located thousands of kilometers from these strategically
important regions have declared them to be zones of vital interest.
"
</P>
<P>
"Attempts are being made to supplant Russia and other states,
particularly Iran, in those regions. But those are the countries
for which the Caspian region and the Caucasus are indeed vitally
important," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said Moscow views the policies of several Western
countries toward the events in Chechnya "as an attempt to limit
Russia's capabilities in the Caucasus."
</P>
<P>
Russian federal troops are in the middle of a major campaign to
root out rebels in the breakaway republic. The military actions
were taken following armed Chechen incursions into neighboring
Daghestan and a spate of terrorist bombings that killed over 300
people in Moscow and two other Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov also criticized a project on the planned Baku-Ceyhan oil
export pipeline as another attempt at forcing Russia out of the
Caucasus. The pipeline would bypass Russia and Iran in
transporting Caspian oil to the West.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, Georgia, Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan signed an agreement
on the U.S.- supported deal in Istanbul, Turkey, during the mid-
November summit of the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
The project is "not viable according to analyses by several
Western experts, and is only being implemented under strong
pressure from the U.S.," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
On Kosovo, the foreign minister said Western countries are
conniving with genocide against non-Albanian residents in the
Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
"Flagrant genocide is being carried out towards ethnic
minorities in Kosovo," he said, noting that some 200,000 Serbs and
other non-Albanians have recently left the region.
</P>
<P>
"Neither Washington, nor Berlin, nor London has voiced any
condemnation of the terrorists' outrages," Ivanov said. "They try
to create the impression that all is normal in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"Such appeasement of Albanian separatists is fraught with dire
consequences for the Balkans," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said Russia will shortly call a session of the U.N.
Security Council to consider the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"As a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council, Russia no
longer intends to tolerate the present situation in Kosovo and
expects the Council to take measures for implementing its
Resolution 1244," he told reporters following a meeting with his
Greek counterpart, George Papandreou.
</P>
<P>
In addition to raising the Kosovo issue at the U.N. Security
Council, Ivanov said, Russia "will use other means at its disposal
to solve the problem," Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
