<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Rises Sharply In November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, November 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer confidence
index rose more than five points to 135.8 in November, up from 130.
5, in October following four monthly declines in a row, The
Conference Board said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, the U.S. prominent research group, said
in a survey that the latest index reading was driven by growing
optimism about economic conditions over the next six months.
</P>
<P>
"A booming economy and a strong job market have consumers in a
confident, free-spending mode," said Lynn Franco, Director of The
Conference Board's Consumer Research Center. "This is reflected in
robust retail spending both on-line and in person. With increasing
numbers of consumers expecting their incomes to rise, it's not
surprising that $4,000 leather bags and 3,000 cashmere coats are
selling briskly, along with $15 Pokemon toys and $25 computer
mouses."
</P>
<P>
Consumers' expectations were up sharply from October, the
research group said, adding that nearly 28 percent of all
consumers anticipate an increase in their incomes, up from 24
percent last months and a smaller percentage of respondents expect
business conditions to worsen.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the labor market was also more optimistic than
last month and 16.4 percent of consumers expect more jobs to be
available in the coming six months, up from 15.9 percent in the
previous survey, it said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. consumer sentiment is an important economic indicator
because consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the nation's
overall economic activity. The consumer confidence index has a
base of 100, set in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
