<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> . Greece Ready to Tackle Y2K Problem, Says Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Greece is fully prepared to
tackle any possible problems caused by the millennium bug or Y2K
in computer and electronic systems in the public sector at the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greece's Interior Minister
Vasso Papandreou said Tuesday that all the procedures required to
make systems year 2000 compliant have been taken by the country's
Public Power Corporation, Public Gas Corporation and Hellenic
Telecommunications Organization.
</P>
<P>
Data current to end-October shows that Greece's national
carrier, the Olympic Airways, is 99 percent year 2000 compliant,
as are the Greek Railways, the Athens and Piraeus Water and Sewage
Company, the stock market and public administration.
</P>
<P>
Greece has contingency plans ready in the event of any problem,
she said, adding that a special operations room has been set up at
the secretariat general for civil protection specifically to deal
with problems related to Y2K.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the secretariat general for consumers said Tuesday
that it will launch an information campaign in December to
reliably inform consumers about the dangers and myths of the
millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will include television and radio spots, the
publication of leaflets, brochures and posters, and the holding of
a special talk on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the campaign is to avoid unnecessary rumor-mongering
about the effect of Y2K on the consumer, and how consumers can
best deal with practical problems they face in tackling the Y2K
problem in relation to personal computers, household appliances
and other small electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
Greece is reportedly among the "moderately prepared" countries
for the millennium bug. 
</P>
</TEXT>
