<HEADLINE> Lebanon Sets Principles for Negotiations with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese parliamentary
committees Tuesday convened to lay down the principles
the country will hold in the future negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Under the chairmanship of House Speaker Nabih Berri and with
the presence of Prime Minister Salim Hoss and Defense Minister
Ghazi Zuetir, the committees of foreign, and security and
defense affairs issued a statement after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The statement said in the future negotiations with Israel,
Lebanon will demand its long-time enemy to implement all
international resolutions calling for an Israeli withdrawal from
occupied Arab lands, including south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been keeping a rein of parts of Lebanon since 1978
and set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in 1985
with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon will be opposed to any agreement regarding Palestinian
refugees at its expense, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Some 360,000 registered Palestinian refugees are living in 12
camps across Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government fears that Palestinian Authority will
settle those refugees in the country in turn for Israeli
acceptance for the establishment of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that Lebanon will also ask Israel to
free all Lebanese held in Israeli jails and compensate for
the damages inflicted during the Israeli agressions to the
country and stop plundering Lebanon's water.
</P>
<P>
In a related development in the same day, European Union
(EU)'s Middle East peace envoy Miguel Angel Moratinos held
talks with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and Hoss.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, the diplomat said the aim of his visit
is to assess the prospects for reviving peace talks on the
Lebanese and Syrian tracks.
</P>
<P>
"We have entered the last stage of the peace process and
it is time for the concerned parties to make difficult
decisions," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos, who came here Monday night, visited Syria and
Jordan last week for the same purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
