<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides Tuesday said although there is a hardening of the
Turkish stance, an international interest still runs high to solve
the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the remarks before his departure to the
U.N. headquarters in New York for the proximity talks scheduled on
December on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Refraining from expressing optimism for the talks sponsored by
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, Clerides said that he will go
to New York for discussions and expects to see if there will be
any response.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Clerides was accompanied by Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides, government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou,
Undersecretary to the President Pantelis Kouros, Attorney-General
Alecos Markides and other officials.
</P>
<P>
The proximity talks will be directed by Annan and by his
representative, Peruvian diplomat Alfonso de Soto.
</P>
<P>
There is little optimism among Cyprus' political circles for
the talks because of Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash's
insistence on the recognition of breakaway republic before direct
talks, which broke down two years ago, can resume. 
</P>
