<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Address Root Causes of Armed Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Tuesday adopted a presidential statement, voicing its
willingness to attach great importance to addressing the root
causes of armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council stresses the importance of a coordinated
international response to economic, social, cultural or
humanitarian problems, which are often the root causes of armed
conflicts," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came at the end of an open debate held by the
Security Council to discuss the 15-nation Council's role in the
prevention of armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"Recognizing the need for the development of effective long-
term strategies, it emphasizes the need for all United Nations
organs and agencies to pursue preventive strategies and to take
action within their respective areas of competence to assist
Member States to eradicate poverty, strengthen development
cooperation and assistance and promote respect for human rights
and fundamental freedoms," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Council emphasizes the need fully to respect and implement
the principles and provisions of the Charter of the United Nations
and norms of international law, in particular in this context
those related to prevention of armed conflicts and settlement of
disputes by peaceful means," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It will give special attention to the humanitarian
consequences of armed conflicts," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council emphasizes the important role of the
Secretary-General in the prevention of armed conflicts," the
statement said. "The Council expresses its readiness to consider
appropriate preventive action in response to the matters brought
to its attention by States or the Secretary-General and which it
deems likely to threaten international peace and security."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council will also consider other preventive
measures such as the establishment of demilitarized zones and
preventive disarmament, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council recognizes the link between the prevention
of armed conflicts, the facilitation of the peaceful settlement of
disputes and the promotion of security for the civilian population,
in particular the protection of human life, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council recognizes the important role that
regional organizations and arrangements are playing in the
prevention of armed conflicts, including through the development
of confidence-and security-building measures," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It emphasizes the importance of cooperation between the United
Nations and regional organizations in preventive activities in
accordance with Chapter VIII of the Charter of the United Nations,
" the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Council welcomes meetings between the United Nations,
including the Security Council, and regional organizations, and
encourages participants to continue to focus those meetings on
issues related to prevention of armed conflicts," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council will also consider the possibility of a
meeting at the level of Foreign Ministers on the issue of the
prevention of armed conflicts during the Millennium Assembly,
which is to be held in September 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, the Security Council has the primary
responsibility for the maintenance of world peace and security, it
therefore, should bear major responsibility in the prevention of
armed conflicts in the world at large. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Introduces Bill to Deter Oil Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has
drawn up a specific environment protection bill to prevent
ecological disaster caused by the oil production in the country, a
government official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Petroleum Botelho de Vasconcelos said the National
Assembly is expected to approve the bill as the ruling People's
Liberation Movement of Angola (MPLA) takes over two-thirds of the
parliamentary seats.
</P>
<P>
It is "extremely important" for the oil producing country to
enact the environment protection law because the oil production,
which is Angola's pillar industry, is prone to bring about
environment pollution, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Although there is no any major ecological disaster happened in
Angola, the government should take precautions against it and
protect the environment for the people, he added.
</P>
<P>
The bill stipulates provisions of the environment protection
for oil producing sector, under which specific institutions will
be set up to cope with major environmental disasters.
</P>
<P>
Angola is the second largest oil producer in Africa with a
daily output of 750,000 barrels, which are mostly from the
off-shore oil fields in the provinces of Zaire and Cabinda.
</P>
</TEXT>
