<HEADLINE> Turkish Economy Falls 6.1 Percent in First Nine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's gross national
product (GNP) shrank by 6.1 percent in the first nine months of
this year, the Turkish State Institute of Statistics (DIE)
revealed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The DIE also said that Turkey's GNP growth rate in the third
quarter of 1999 was a negative 6.6 percent, Turkish Daily News
reported.
</P>
<P>
From January to September this year, the DIE said, Turkey's
agricultural sector output fell by 5.1 percent, industry 5.7
percent, construction 6.1 percent, commerce 8.3 percent,
communications and transport 2.8 percent, self-employed businesses
4.8 percent and import tax 11.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
It said, however, that financial services grew by 5.9 percent,
ownership of dwellings 1.7 percent and government services 3.0
percent.
</P>
<P>
DIE did not give the causes for the decline, but it is widely
believed that earthquakes contributed a great deal to the plunge.
</P>
