<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Pledges to Curb HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian President Negaso
Gidada said Tuesday that his country will do its best to curb the
spread of HIV/ AIDS.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to mark the World AIDS Day which falls on
Wednesday, Negaso said that the Ethiopian government was ready to
work together with the public at large in the fight against the
pandemic.
</P>
<P>
A five-year national program has been formulated to tackle the
socio- economic as well as the psychological problems generated by
HIV/AIDS, Negaso said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, preparations were well underway to establish
a governmental secretarial office and national council charged
with the task of coordinating the implementation of the program.
</P>
<P>
The president also called on the governmental and
non-governmental organizations, religious institutions, the mass
media as well as the public to join hands in the fight against
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
According to Negaso, more than 33 million people across the
world have been infected with the virus that causes AIDS, of which
22.5 million live in Sub-Sahara African countries.
</P>
<P>
There are about three million people living with HIV in
Ethiopia, he said. The coming World AIDS Day will be observed
under the theme "Let us talk and learn about HIV/AIDS with
children and the youth openly". 
</P>
