<HEADLINE> Iranian Parliament to Probe into Serial Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Majlis (parliament)
has formed a 15-strong investigation team to probe into the
serial political killings of writers and intellectuals late last
year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of parliamentary reporters, Ali Movahedi
Savoji, chairman of the Majlis commission of councils and internal
affairs, said on Tuesday the investigation team is expected to
start work next week.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 parliamentarians from different political factions
signed a petition earlier this year asking for an
investigation of the spate of political murders last year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In November and December last year, the leader of the Iran
Nation Party Darius Forouhar and his wife were stabbed to death
at home and at least three dissident writers were mysteriously
killed in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Intelligence Ministry announced in January that some
of its own agents were involved in the political murders.
The revelation triggered an intense political quarrel between the
conservative and moderate factions and forced former Intelligence
Minister Qorbanali Dorri Najafabadi to resign.
</P>
<P>
Former Deputy Intelligence Minister for Political and Security
Affairs Saeed Emami was believed to be the mastermind behind
the political killings. But Emami committed suicide in prison
June by taking in depilatory substance while taking a bath.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Judicial Organization of the Iranian Armed
Forces Mohammad Niazi said earlier that a total of 23 people
have been arrested in connection with the political killings
while 33 others have been summoned for questioning.
</P>
<P>
However, some local dailies alleged that Emami was not the
highest agent behind the political killings, because he had no
right to issue religious verdicts against dissident writers.
</P>
<P>
Savoji said that according to the Majlis statute on the
subject, all the agencies and institutions which are in
possession of papers and documents concerning the serial murders
have to deliver them to the investigating team.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the investigating team would refrain from
divulging certain confidential and secret information, but a
major part of the subject should not be considered as secret.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome any assistance on the part of the colleagues and
officials in performing this mission," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
