<HEADLINE> Uganda Hails Rebirth of East African Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has hailed the remarkable progress East Africa has
achieved in resurrecting the regional community, according to a
press release issued by the Presidential Office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony of the treaty for the rebirth
of the East African Community (EAC) in Arusha, Tanzania Tuesday
afternoon, Museveni said by signing the treaty, the three East
African countries have expressed their readiness to exploit
together available opportunities for the development of the
people.
</P>
<P>
The development of modern economy demands bigger markets for
processed products. The three countries of Tanzania, Kenya and
Uganda in the region have fulfilled the demands of the Lagos Plan
of Action which called for bigger markets to facilitate
development, he observed.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EAC, now with a population of about 100
million, will necessitate the enactment of policies that can help
people get out of poverty and facilitate private entrepreneurs to
do trade and business.
</P>
<P>
He also thanked the leaders of the member states for making a
step forwards in the political federation of East Africa, saying
economic integration measures should be the basis of steps towards
political integration.
</P>
<P>
At the function, the Ugandan president emphasized the
importance of economically empowering the people so that they get
out of poverty and benefit from an expanding market.
</P>
<P>
The former East African Community was founded in 1967 and fell
out in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's signing of the treaty is regarded as a big step
towards the re- creation of the regional bloc which is expected to
bind the three countries more closely in politics, economy,
culture and defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
