<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects U.S. Allegation on Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Asefi said that the Islamic Republic of Iran has been
among victims of terrorism, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Such baseless propaganda campaign of the U.S. is a threadbare
tactic which has proved to be futile two decades after the
establishment of the Islamic Republic of Iran in 1979, he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin on Monday accused
Iran of reneging on promises to abandon support for terrorism in
an attempt to destroy hopes among Arabs and Israelis for a
comprehensive peace.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said senior Iranian officials have publicly
denounced terrorism and it is "reasonable for us to expect that
the actions and policies of the Islamic Republic (of Iran)
should reflect these statements."
</P>
<P>
He accused Iran of encouraging terrorist activities involving
the Iran-backed Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas and several radical
Palestinian groups, including Hamas in the Palestinian West Bank
and Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
"We have made clear to Iran that there cannot be an
improvement in relations until Iran takes meaningful steps to
end its support for terrorism and cooperates in the fight
against terrorism," Rubin said, "there cannot be a lifting of
the sanctions we imposed in the absence of meaningful steps
to those ends."
</P>
<P>
However, the Iranian spokesman said that Iran supports the
Palestinian nation in their efforts to restore their rights
and liberate their own land.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. claim against Iran is repeated at a time when
the Israeli prime minister openly opposes the return of the
Palestinian refugees to their homeland, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asefi underlined that ignoring the natural rights of the
Palestinian refugees to return to their homeland along with
keeping silence vis-a-vis the Israeli expansionist policies,
brings into question the U.S. sincerity in its support for
peace in the Middle East. 
</P>
