<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Conditionally Approves Exxon, Mobil Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government
approved Tuesday the 81-billion-U.S.-dollar merger of Exxon and
Mobil, creating the world's largest privately owned petroleum
company.
</P>
<P>
In a 4-0 vote, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) approved an
agreement under which the new company will sell more than 2,400
service stations mostly in the Northeast, California and Texas to
ensure retail competition where the two companies have large,
overlapping market shares.
</P>
<P>
The new company will be called Exxon-Mobil and be based in
Irving, Texas.
</P>
<P>
When Exxon, the country's largest oil producer, and Mobil,
which is the second largest, announced the merger a year ago,
federal regulators and members of Congress voiced concern about
potential anti-competitive problems, especially in retail gasoline
sales in some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
To address those concerns, the two companies agreed to demands
by the FTC that they sell off about 15 percent of their retail
outlets -- or 2,413 service stations -- mostly in New England, the
mid-Atlantic states, Texas and California -- where the two
companies in some areas control 20 to 35 percent of the retail
market.
</P>
<P>
Exxon also will have to sell a refinery near Benicia,
California, some petroleum terminal areas and pipeline assets, the
FTC said.
</P>
<P>
Without such divestitures, the merger "would significantly
injure competition" in the areas of retail sales and in oil
refining in California, the FTC concluded.
</P>
<P>
While the FTC order reflects the most extensive divestitures in
the agency's history, they still represent only a small portion of
the two companies' nearly 16,000 gasoline stations and 138 billion
dollars in combined assets.
</P>
<P>
The two companies have said the merger was needed to reduce
costs and compete with the huge, low-cost government-owned oil
companies in Saudi Arabia, Iran, Mexico and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Savings from the merger are projected at 2.8 billion dollars a
year and about 9,000 jobs will be cut from the combined firm's 123,
000 employees worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
