<HEADLINE> U.S. Says No Objection to European Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday that it had no objection to moves by Germany and France to
develop a force within NATO as that would relieve the United
States of lion's share of the military burden.
</P>
<P>
"We're encouraged, we're supportive, we're welcoming of efforts
by key European allies, those who have the capability or the
potential to improve their capability," State Department spokesman
James Rubin said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
France and Germany issued a communiqu on Tuesday at a one-day
summit that the two countries support a new force that would
intervene in circumstances that did not affect the Atlantic
alliance as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The circumstance were not spelled out, nor was how much say
other NATO members would have in the new force's missions.
</P>
<P>
France and Germany also want to boost Europe's military air
capabilities and recommended creation of a European air transport
command.
</P>
<P>
"In general, we support a stronger European defense that will
strengthen the trans-Atlantic relationship. That was a key goal
laid out at the NATO summit, the 50th anniversary, last spring,"
Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
