<HEADLINE> WTO Ministerial Opening Delayed Due to Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The opening ceremony of the
World Trade Organization (WTO) Ministerial Conference had to be
delayed due to large-scale demonstrations here in downtown Seattle,
and anti-riot police fired tear-gas to disperse crowds of
protesters who have blocked all entrances to the venue of the
trade summit.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of protesters have gathered since early this morning
around the Paramount Theater, where the opening ceremony was
originally to be held at 10:00 this morning,. The opening session
has been postponed as many delegates have been unable to break the
pitch line and get into the conference hall.
</P>
<P>
Many of the 2500 foreign and local correspondents have also
been kept way from the Media Center at the Washington State
Convention and Trade Center, since almost all entrances to the
Media Center were blocked by the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, mainly college students, unionists, human
rights advocates and green party activists, chanted anti-WTO
slogans, and sang and danced at the major intersections in the
downtown area, preventing delegates and journalists from getting
into the meeting venue.
</P>
<P>
A foreign diplomat complained that he had to walk for 20
minutes to get into the conference hall, an experience he had
never had before in his career.
</P>
<P>
There are reports that a Colombian delegation headed by foreign
trade minister Martha Lucia Ramirez was attacked by demonstrators
who banged on the roof of their car.
</P>
<P>
"Delegates are being assaulted and they're being bussed to the
convention center, " Reuters quoted a policeman as saying.
</P>
<P>
The situation got intensified at noon, as some demonstrators
smashed shop windows on the street, and in some areas police
scuffled with protesters, and were forced to use pepper spray to
push away the protesting crowd.
</P>
<P>
"The free trade policy of the WTO hurt workers in this country,
and we're worried that our living standards would be lowered down
as more imports from foreign countries flush in," Ryan Fleglo, a
college student protester, told Xinhua corespondent, who
maneuvered to get into the Media Center after milling round for
almost one hour outside the building.
</P>
<P>
Unionists have tried hard to add the matter of labor standards
to the WTO ministerial agenda, an issue that has been opposed by
most developing countries as a hidden protectionism by rich
countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said on Tuesday he sympathized with
protesters at the WTO meeting in Seattle and that trade agreements
should take into consideration labor and environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
An Asian journalist said that the U.S. condolence makes one
doubt that it is trying to make use of the public protest as a
leverage to gain up-hand on such contentious issues as labor and
environment in the new round of trade talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
