<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Dismisses Hubbub over Panama Canal Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
on Tuesday that he did not believe Hong Kong-based Hutchison
Whampoa's control of the Panama Canal could hurt national security
once the United States cedes control at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. politicians have recently raised a hubbub that
Hutchison Whampoa is a company that has ties to Beijing and its
win of the right of management of the ports at both ends of the
canal could harm U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
Retired Adm. Thomas Moore, a former chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, even made sensational remarks earlier this week
that China was plotting to take over the canal once the United
States relinquishes control and use the area to launch a nuclear
attack on America.
</P>
<P>
Clinton dismissed all those notions, saying he would "very
surprised if any adverse consequences flowed from the Chinese
running the canal."
</P>
<P>
"I think the Chinese will in fact be bending over backward to
make sure that they run it in a competent and able and fair manner,
" Clinton told a news conference at the White House.
</P>
<P>
"This is like them -- is like China coming into the World Trade
Organization. I'll think they'll want to demonstrate to a distant
part of the world that they can be a responsible partner," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He also said he was confident the Panamanian government would
run the canal in an appropriate fashion and reiterated his support
of the handover on Dec. 31, which would end a 96-year U.S.
military presence in Panama.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's the right thing to do," Clinton said. "I think
that the new government of Panama is committed to maintaining the
canal in an appropriate way and keeping it open and working with
us to do so and having good relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Former President Jimmy Carter and Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright will head a U.S. delegation to attend the
ceremony of handover of the canal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
