<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Milestone in East African Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and
Uganda signed a treaty here Tuesday to revive the defunct East
African Community (EAC), making a big stride forward on the
tortuous road of regional integration.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa and Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni fixed their signature
on the 153-article treaty which will decide the destiny of 80
million people residing in an area of 1.8 million square
kilometers facing the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The three Kiswahili-speaking states have enjoyed a long history
of cooperation featured by the Customs Union between kenya and
Uganda in 1917, which Tanzania (then Tanganyika) joined in 1927.
</P>
<P>
Beginning from this, the three neighbors then moved forward to
form the East African High Commission (1948-1961), the East
African Common Services Organization (1961-1967) and the
well-known East African Community (1967- 1977) or EAC.
</P>
<P>
However, the first EAC, in spite of its unremitting exploration
for regional cooperation and development, collapsed in 1977 as
great changes took place due to both internal and external factors
which were not supportive of regional integration at that time.
</P>
<P>
As the time entered the 1990s when a trend of regional
cooperation ran high, Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda were encouraged
to revive the defunct EAC by setting up a Permanent Tripartite
Commission for East African Cooperation on November 30,1993.
</P>
<P>
The commission launched a secretariat at its headquarters in
Arusha on March 14,1996 to coordinate and boost economic,
political and social development in the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Since its founding, the commission had tried to address the
shortcomings inherent in the past cooperation initiatives by
implementing practical policies including a Development Strategy
(1997-2000).
</P>
<P>
It also, among other measures, issued the East African
passports to facilitate the inter-state movement of people,
achieved agreement on unity of the customs by 2000 and adopted a
pact on defense cooperation, forging ahead into finalization of
the reestablishment of a new community.
</P>
<P>
As a milestone in regional integration, the new EAC will expand
and deepen its economic, political and social cooperation among
the partner states for mutual benefits at a higher level.
</P>
<P>
Under the Treaty for Establishment of the East African
Community, a Customs Union will be set up, followed by a Common
Market, a Monetary Union and ultimately a Political Federation of
the East African States.
</P>
<P>
To achieve these ambitions, the EAC pins hope on its main
organs including the Summit of Heads of State, the Council of
Ministers, the Coordination Committee, the Sectoral Committees,
the East African Court of Justice, the East African Legislative
Assembly and the Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
In order to avoid the same old road to ruin, the new EAC is
determined to base its strategy on a people-centered, private and
market economy, discarding the practice of governmental control
over every field.
</P>
<P>
It will spare no efforts in mobilizing the enthusiasm of all
sectors, all organizations and all social strata to promote
development in all fields and absorb foreign investment in an
enabling environment.
</P>
<P>
To carry out the role of guidance, coordination and promotion
on basic strategies, the EAC has prepared a 26-point action plan
on the implementation of the treaty with a period of six months to
four years.
</P>
<P>
In their speeches after the signing of the treaty, the three
presidents reaffirmed that the new EAC will work closely with
other African regional organizations towards the achievement of
the proposed African Economic Community.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the promotion of peace and security and
observance of the principle of peaceful resolution of conflicts in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that abounding with natural, material and
human resources, the three East African states have, through more
than 30 years' efforts, laid down a primary economic structure
linked by a network of roads, railways, waterways and airlines as
well as seaports, which will contribute to their future
development.
</P>
<P>
With a solid economic foundation in Kenya, a steady economic
development in Tanzania and an up-and-coming economic growth in
Uganda, the EAC partner states can well complement each other in
their common development, they said.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that a reviving EAC, with its door opening to
other states, will also contribute to the development in the Great
Lakes region and the African continent as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
