<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End In Mixed Mood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The London stock market's three-
day closing highs ended Tuesday as the FTSE-100 remained stuck in
negative territory.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark index was set lower by a poor performance on Wall
Street Monday night and by nerves ahead of next week's interest
rate decision by the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
The index failed to register the bullish mood of U.S. blue
chips and fell 1.4 percent, snapping a three-day winning streak,
to end at 6,597.2, a fall of 95 points.
</P>
<P>
The telecom sector wiped 32 points off the index, Cable &AMP;
Wireless was one of biggest losers of the session as it slumped 9.
6 percent. British Telecom fell 4.2 percent, while Vodafone closed
almost flat.
</P>
<P>
Heavyweight banking and drug stocks were all weak, with HSBC
down 4.3 percent, and SmithKline Beecham down 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 ended off its session lows, but still fell
0.6 percent, or 32 points, to end at 5,341.62, its second
consecutive negative close after a series of record finishes.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Xetra Dax ended high right at the close, having spent
most of the session well inside negative territory. The index
finished 7 points higher at 5,896.04.
</P>
<P>
Heavyweight Deutsche Telekom was largely responsible for the
late turnaround of the index as it shrugged off earlier losses in
excess of 3 percent to close 0.5 percent higher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
