<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Compensation Approved For Cermis Disaster Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Final approval was given Tuesday
to compensation for the families of the 20 people killed in
February 1998 when a U.S. Marine jet sliced a ski-lift cable in
northern Italy, sending a cable-car hurtling to the ground.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Senate defense committee gave its definitive green
light to a law earmarking 76 billion lire (about 40 million U.S.
dollars) for the indemnity which will see each victim's family
receive up to 3.8 billion lire (about 2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Today we have honored a commitment," said Italian vice-Defense
Minister Massimo Brutti, "a terrible injustice was inflicted on
innocent people and the state must do what is in its power."
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the London Convention covering NATO
operations and liabilities in a NATO country, compensation for the
disaster will be paid by the Italian Defense Ministry and then
shared between Italy(25 percent) and the U.S. (75 percent), the
country whose military personnel were responsible for the act.
</P>
<P>
The measure passed Tuesday also envisages the appointment of a
special commissioner to assess and authorize other claims.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first major step on the way to winning a just
compensation for the damages," said Alessandro Comola and Alberto
Mioni, lawyers for the families of the three Italians killed.
</P>
<P>
The disaster occurred when the tail-fin of a U.S. Marine EA-6B
Prowler surveillance plane sliced the Cermis ski-lift cable during
a ground-hugging training flight out of the NATO air-base at
nearby Italian northeastern town of Aviano.
</P>
<P>
As well as the three Italians, seven Germans, five Belgians,
two Poles, two Austrians and one Dutch citizen were killed in the
incident.
</P>
<P>
There have also been separate claims for compensation from the
town of Cavalese in the Dolomites, where the disaster happened and
from the owner-operator of the ski-lift, which runs up the flank
of Mount Cermis.
</P>
<P>
These claims, totaling some 44 billion lire (about 23 million U.
S.dollars), will be handled separately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
