<HEADLINE> Shares Fall in Tokyo on Weak Information, High-tech Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed lower in
Tokyo Wednesday, dragged down by weak information, telecom and
high-tech issues.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 62.28 points, or 0.34
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 18,495.95.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 30.22 points or 1.84 percent to 1,
611.31.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to 710.05 million shares
from Tuesday's 673.53 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were lower in 15 of the 33 business sectors.
</P>
<P>
The electric machinery sector fell 2.65 percent, reflecting
Tuesday's plunge in the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The information and telecom sector, which faced selling
following its recent sharp gains, was the biggest loser, declining
7.86 percent, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the biggest winner was the pulp and paper industry,
surging 6.10 percent, as they can import materials for their
products cheaply under the strong yen, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 666 to 554 despite the falls in the Nikkei and the TOPIX
indexes, with 119 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
