<HEADLINE> Kenyan Newspapers Hail EAC Rebirth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Major newspapers in Kenya
Wednesday highlighted the signing the East African Community (EAC)
treaty and hailed it as "a milestone for the three African
nations."
</P>
<P>
The papers said the treaty is a major step toward a new
regional body aiming to eventually achieve economic and political
integration.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania signed the EAC
treaty in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha Tuesday amid sounds
of festive music and the sight of hundreds of balloons floating
skywards.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial entitled "Let's keep the EAC train right on
track", the Daily Nation said it heralds a major turning point in
relations between the three east African neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The editorial says the new treaty provides for a common east
African passport and flag, economic and monetary integration,
among other joint projects, reflecting "the wishes of the people
to enhance their social, cultural, political and economic
well-being."
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper said that the new treaty
saw the rebirth of the East African Community which was disbanded
22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the treaty would combine the advantages of the
three countries together as Kenya is strong in manufactured goods
and industry, Tanzania's mineral and power sectors are stronger,
and Uganda has advantages in agricultural sector and energy
potential.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times said the treaty would boost the regional trade,
urging the commitment to the implementation of the stipulations of
the treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
