<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
news items in leading Turkish newspapers on Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said that the country's
power shortage problem would be solved as the Blue Stream project
is to go into effect.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the Institute of State Planning (DPT) is
supervising the financial resources of Turkey, but we need to act
bolder."
</P>
<P>
Ecevit noted that Russian natural gas reached Turkey through a
pipeline traversing Ukraine, Moldavia, Romania and Bulgaria, and
these countries sometimes consume more than their share and this
has caused the power shortage problem in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey's overdependence on Russia, its major natural gas
supplier, has left the country in the dark and cold and may cause
further havoc this winter unless Ankara acts quickly to diversify
its gas sources.
</P>
<P>
Power cuts were imposed Monday in Ankara for two hours a day to
save energy after the supply of Russian gas fell.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Turkish Pipeline Company said due to cold
weather in Russia and Ukraine, Moscow had only been able to
supply Turkey with 20 million cubic meters of gas per day, down
from the usual 27 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The interruption left Turkey's gas-fired power plant short of
energy and thus led to water shortages in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- Moody's, an institution for evaluating ratings of
creditability of banking, has increased the creditability grade of
Turkish banks to "positive", thus enabling Turkey to attract more
easily foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Turkish banks have suffered from creditability losses after the
country's 1994 economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
