<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Leaves Singapore for Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
left here on Wednesday afternoon for Vietnam, the last stop of his
four-ASEAN nation trip, after ending a successful official visit
to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Zhu arrived in Singapore on Monday after his official visits to
Malaysia and the Philippines where he also attended the informal
summit meetings between ASEAN and China, Japan and South Korea,
and between ASEAN and China.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay in Singapore, the Chinese premier
held talks with Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong. The two
leaders reached a consensus on further enhancing the two
countries' cooperation in various fields and exchanged views on
regional and international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also called on Singapore President S.R. Nathan and met with
Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew and the two sides held friendly
talks.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday at the 17th Singapore Lecture which saw the
attendance of his Singapore counterpart Goh Chok Tong and other
senior government officials, Zhu delivered a policy speech
entitled "China and Asia in the New Century."
</P>
<P>
He was also briefed Tuesday by senior officials from the
Temasek Holdings (Pte) Ltd, a Singapore government-linked company,
on matters concerning the operation of the company.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday morning, Zhu toured public housing complexes built
by the Singapore government specially for ordinary Singaporeans
and visited some Singaporean families there.
</P>
<P>
Then he paid a visit to Jurong Island, a 7-billion-Singapore-
dollar (about 4.8 billion U.S. dollars) project undertaken by the
Singapore government to merge seven southern islands into a single
land mass to develop a world-class chemical hub.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two countries shared the confidence that Premier
Zhu's visit will surely further push forward the development of
Sino-Singapore relations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu left Singapore with an entourage which included Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan, Special Assistant Liu Huaqiu and Vice
Governor of People's Bank of China Yan Haiwang.
</P>
<P>
Seeing the Chinese premier and his wife Lao An off at the
Changi International Airport were Singapore Minister without
Portfolio Lim Boon Heng, other senior Singapore government
officials and Chinese Ambassador to Singapore Chen Baoliu.
</P>
</TEXT>
