<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Destroy World War II Gas Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Twenty four gas bombs left
behind by Japanese invaders in China during World War II will be
destroyed in Heilongjiang Province, northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The gas bombs were discovered in a rolling mill in Lindian
County, about 70 kilometers away from the oil-producing city of
Daqing. One of them, 155 mm in diameter, is the first of its kind
ever found in China.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Shenyang Military Area Command said that the
poison gas may have leaked from some of the deformed dud gas bombs.
</P>
<P>
Documents in the Lindian County Archives Bureau show that in
November 1931, Japanese planes dropped bombs on Lindian County.
Many civilians died and property was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Inhaling the poisonous gas could cause people to choke to death
or cause incurable skin diseases and cancer.
</P>
<P>
Workers of the Lindian Rolling Mill found Japanese bombs in
1992 when collecting scrap iron and steel. They have discovered
two tons of bombs since them.
</P>
<P>
But no one knew that there were gas bombs buried under until
May this year when people were astonished as experts from the
Shenyang Military Area Command excavated them.
</P>
<P>
According to the military experts, the bombs were covered with
layers of rust and contained either mustard gas or chlorine. The
rest of the two tons of bombs have been transported by carriage to
a county suburb and detonated after being buried in two three-
meter-deep pits.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 Chinese have been injured by chemical weapons
left behind by Japanese troops and some of them have died due to
the chemical weapons, according to a 400-page report from the
Heilongjiang People's Publishing House, "History of Japan's
Chemical War".
</P>
<P>
Japan began its chemical weapons research in 1915 and used
chemical weapons on a large scale during China's War of Resistance
against Japan (1937-1945).
</P>
<P>
After World War II, many chemical weapons were left behind in
China by Japanese troops, and the location and exact number of the
chemical weapons are still unknown, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
For the past four decades, chemical weapons have been
discovered in many places in China. In 1991, about 50 gas bombs
excavated at high school in Hebei Province, north China, injured
some 20 students.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Parliament Backs Amnesty Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Members of Parliament (MPs) in
Uganda Tuesday overwhelmingly supported the Amnesty Bill 1999
intended to pardon rebels fighting the government and their
collaborators.
</P>
<P>
The House, presided over by Deputy Speaker Edward Ssekandi, was
 characterized by passionate appeals for openness and
reconciliation, the New Vision daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill provides for the re-integration of rebels into society
 through an Amnesty Commission and a Demobilization and
Resettlement Team, both to be appointed by President Yoweri
Museveni.
</P>
<P>
The bill, moved by Minister of Internal Affairs Edward
Rugumayo, is intended to replace the 1987 Amnesty Statute that has
since expired.
</P>
<P>
Some MPs argued that the amnesty should include government
soldiers who committed atrocities against sections of the
population and all persons who have been tried or convicted for
treason.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Parliamentary Affairs Rebecca Kadaaga said the bill
was preceded by a wide consultative process and the victims
expressed readiness to forgive everybody for the sake of peace.
</P>
<P>
During a tour of the north region earlier this year, President
Museveni said that he would pardon the rebels if they come out
peacefully and surrender to the government. With the steps taken
to normalize relations with Sudan, the rebels in the north would
be left with squeezed space for operation and survival.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has now two main rebel groups fighting the government.
The Allied Democratic Forces and Lord Resistance Army maim, abduct
and kill in the western and northern parts of the country
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
