<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Accelerate Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government has moved to speed up the pace of privatization with
several significant new initiatives in telecommunications,
forestry and defense, Business Day newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South African Telekom would be listed by 2001 ahead of its
telephone monopoly ending in May 2002, South African Public
Enterprises Minister Jeff Radebe was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Four preferred bidders had been selected for the state's
commercial forests, and the South Africa Special Risks Association
was to be sold immediately.
</P>
<P>
The decision were taken at a Monday meeting of the
inter-ministerial cabinet committee, a forum of ministers which
decides on privatization.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said President Thabo Mbeki had made it
clear privatization is a key tenet of government's macro-economic
policy, and the acceleration of the program is a priority.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts have attributed the decrease of foreign direct
investment in South Africa last year to the slowdown of the
privatization process. 
</P>
