<HEADLINE> U.S. Says No Comment on Spying Diplomat Detained in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
confirmed Tuesday one of its diplomats had been involved in "an
incident" in Russia but declined to comment further on what Moscow
describes him as a spy.
</P>
<P>
"Other than confirming that there was an accident involving an
American working at the U.S.embassy, I'm not going to comment on
alleged intelligence matters," State Department Spokesman James
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He also declined to comment on whether the arrest was in
retaliation for charges made against a navy officer in the United
States who was accused of passing secrets to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Security office said earlier in the day that Cheri
Leberknight, a political attache at the U.S. embassy in Moscow,
worked for the CIA and was caught red-handed while collecting
secret military information from a Russian citizen. 
