<HEADLINE> Manila Encourages Vigilance Against AIDS: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- As the Philippines joined the
international community Wednesday in observing the World AIDS Day,
the Philippine government encouraged the public to do their part
in controlling the spread of the disease in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here, Health Secretary Albert
Romualdez emphasized the need for tighter surveillance against the
entry here of carriers of the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome
(AIDS) virus.
</P>
<P>
"We must make sure that AIDS virus carries from other countries
do not come here," Romualdez said.
</P>
<P>
He said the danger of AIDS is relatively high in other
Southeast Asian countries, such as in Thailand and the border
areas of Malaysia, Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The risk of AIDS in the Philippines is not as high as in India
or Africa, he said, adding that the Philippine government is still
intent on improving that situation.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez said the government regularly conducts AIDS tests on
high-risk groups, and monitors carriers of the AIDS-causing virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
