<HEADLINE> Zimbawe Adopts National AIDS Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Parliament of Zimbabwe passed a
bill Tuesday to set up a National AIDS Council to provide for
policy direction and coordination in the fight against HIV/AIDS,
the Herald daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Steering the National AIDS Council Bill, Minister of Health and
Child Welfare Timothy Stamps said a number of non-governmental
organizations and community-based care groups are complementing
the efforts of the government.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen members appointed by President Robert Mugabe will
control the council. They come from health care, industry and
commerce, media, religion, traditional medicine, trade unions and
law.
</P>
<P>
The president is scheduled to launch a national AIDS policy
Wednesday, also the International AIDS Day, seeking to put checks
and balances on dealing with the pandemic, the paper said.!!
</P>
<P>
But to contain the further spread of HIV/AIDS and enhance the
fight against the pandemic, there is need to centralize the
efforts of all the non-governmental organizations to maximize
utilization of resources.
</P>
<P>
This requires the setting up of a high profile body to
coordinate efforts to fight HIV/AIDS, Stamps said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is second to Botswana on the world list of countries
worst affected by AIDS.  Cumulative AIDS cases in Zimbabwe
since 1985 are estimated to be 650,000. About 1.4 million adults
are thought to be infected with HIV. 
</P>
</TEXT>
