<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Benefit From Regional Coop Against Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- African countries have benefited
from regional cooperation through joint crime fighting operation
targeted at areas such as car thefts, illegal trafficking in
firearms and drug trafficking, an International Police (Interpol)
official has said.
</P>
<P>
Vice-president of African region of the Interpol, Augustine
Chihuri, said this at the fourth African regional meeting on the
Traffic in Stolen Motor Vehicles which was attended by 16 African
and three European countries in Harare Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the regional operations have not completely wiped out
car thefts, they have instilled fear in the hearts of the most
hardened criminals, said Chihuri, who is also Zimbabwe's
Commissioner of Police.
</P>
<P>
"This fear is an important crime fighting tool because
criminals must be kept on their toes all the time," Zimbabwean
media Wednesday quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They have to realize that no country is prepared to be a haven
for crooks and that the interests of one country are entwined with
those of the next," Chihuri said.
</P>
<P>
He urged participants at the meeting to come up with concrete
measures in the areas of extradition, repatriation, gathering of
intelligence and border controls.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized the need for other relevant government
departments such as customs, immigration and vehicle registration
to attend meetings of this nature.
</P>
<P>
The private sector, such as manufacturers, car hire companies
and the insurance industry also had to be part of the meetings, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Each one of us has a role to play in providing vital
identification information on cars and the upgrading of
anti-vehicle theft devices, as well as providing the necessary
sponsorship to come up with crime fighting platforms such as this
meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC), through
Interpol, this month agreed to introduce a single clearance
vehicle certificate by the turn of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
It was hoped the move would curb the proliferation of cases
involving cross border vehicle theft in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
