<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Ex-Intelligence Leader Sentenced Two Years in Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Ulan Bator Court ruled
Tuesday to maintain the judgment by the city's district court of
two-year imprisonment to the country's former intelligence agency
director for abuse of power, a news report said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On September 21, the district court sentenced Jaalkhuu Baatar,
former director of the Central Intelligence Agency of Mongolia, to
two years in jail because he had been found to abuse his power in
1996 to order the surveillance and wiretap over some members of
the State Great Hural (parliament), newspaper Daily News reported.
</P>
<P>
Baatar then appealed to the Ulan Bator Court on October 20.
</P>
<P>
This has been the first case in the history of Mongolia to
sentence a leader of the country's security department.
</P>
<P>
In November 1996, the parliamentary group of the Mongolian
People's Revolutionary Party sued Baatar for his order to wire tap
and supervise some of the party leaders and members and asked the
Great Hural to investigate the major general.
</P>
<P>
The government dismissed Baatar in December after an
investigation and changed the name of the Central Intelligence
Agency into the National Security Protection Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
