<HEADLINE> 4 Killed in Plane Crash Near Melbourne, Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Four people were killed in a
light plane crash just Northwest of Melbourne in Southeast
Australia Wednesday afternoon, police and the rural ambulance
service said.
</P>
<P>
The four were on board a Cessna 172 when it came down in a
paddock off the Kilmore Road, four kilometers out of Gisborne,
just after 2.30 p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
Police and ambulance service have confirmed all four on board
died. The coroner and Australian Transport Safety Bureau
investigators are on their way to the crash site.
</P>
<P>
It is still not known where the plane was flying to or from,
whether it was trying to land at a nearby airfield, or make an
emergency landing in the paddock.
</P>
<P>
Gisborne is about 50 kilometers Northwest of Melbourne. A small
airfield is at Riddells Creek near Gisborne.
</P>
<P>
Rural ambulance spokesman Paul Bird said ambulance crews
responded within minutes but could do nothing once they arrived.
</P>
<P>
"It's my understanding from our people when they got there was
no-one left alive," he told 3AW radio.
</P>
<P>
A motorist driving past after the accident said the plane
landed in the paddock about 500 meters from the road.
</P>
<P>
"It's still pretty much together, it looks like it was trying
to land because it's in the middle of the paddock," the motorist
told 3AW.
</P>
<P>
"(The wreckage) doesn't look too bad from the road," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghai to Build Three Museums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Qinghai
Province has decided to build three museums to promote its tourism,
local tourism officials announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The first will be the Qinghai Lake Museum, which will feature a
long history of the lake's formation, transformation and
ecological resources.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai Lake, the largest inland saltwater lake in China,
is a State-level natural reserve. It has long been considered by
local ethnic Tibetan people as a "divine lake".
</P>
<P>
Liuwan Museum of Ancient Painted Pottery will be the second
museum the province plans to build. It will display over 30,000
items of ancient painted pottery excavated from the site of the
Liuwan ruins since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The third will be the Tubo Culture Museum, which features a
store of valuable relics uncovered from ancient tombs built during
the rule of Tubo, a regime established by ethnic groups in the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau between the 7th and 9th century.
</P>
<P>
Besides grasslands and lakes with hundreds of bird species,
Qinghai also hosts numerous Buddhist temples, monasteries and
other sites of historical interest.
</P>
<P>
The province hosted 16,600 overseas tourists last year, earning
30.18 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese President Leaves to Visit India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese President Tran Duc
Luong and his wife left here Wednesday for a five-day official
visit to India at the invitation of Indian President K.R.
Narayanan.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which is the first by a Vietnamese president to
India since the two countries established diplomatic ties in 1972,
aims at strengthening the multi-form cooperation between the two
countries, particularly in agriculture, information technology and
personnel training.
</P>
<P>
Luong is being accompanied by Deputy Prime Minster Pham Gia
Khiem, Defense Minister Pham Van Tra, Health Minister Do Nguyen
Phuong, Deputy Foreign Minister Nguyen Dinh Bin and Director of
the President's Office Nguyen Canh Dinh and other high-ranking
officials.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Party daily Nhan Dan (People) Wednesday carried an
editorial, describing the visit as marking a new step in Vietnam's
expanding external relations with the South Asian region,
especially India.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Vietnam and India were kicked off with a Vietnam
visit by India's first prime minister J. Nehru as early as in
October 1954 and an India visit by Vietnam's first president Ho
Chi Minh in February 1958.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have signed cooperation agreements on trade,
avoidance of double taxation, encouragement and protection of
investment, civil aviation, ore mining, culture, science,
technology, environment and traditional medicine.
</P>
<P>
The two-way trade turnover averaged 140 million U.S. dollars a
year in the 1994-97 period, according to a report of Vietnam News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam exported rice, food seasoning, black tea and plastic
products to India while importing western medicines, car rubber
inner tubes and tires, tools and equipment, chemicals and wheat
flour.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997 trade between the two countries has slightly slowed
down with Vietnam incurring a large trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
India has been among the earliest investors in Vietnam since
1980, but so far it has invested just 36.8 million U.S. dollars in
seven projects mainly in agriculture and farm produce processing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0114 </DOCNO>
