<HEADLINE> Myanmar Reiterates Support for Regional Rural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Myanmar official
Tuesday reiterated full support for and cooperation with the
activities of the Center on Integrated Rural Development for Asia
and the Pacific (CIRDAP).
</P>
<P>
Major-General Nyunt Tin, Myanmar minister of agriculture and
irrigation, made the remarks here at the opening session of the
20th regular meeting of the executive committee of the CIRDAP,
attended by delegates of the center's member nations, official
newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As an active member country of the CIRDAP, Myanmar is providing
its strong support for and actively participating in the center's
development activities, he said, adding that efforts are being
made for rural development and poverty eradication through
national programs.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of developing Myanmar's agricultural
sector, based on which all-round development of other sectors of
the economy is to be brought about.
</P>
<P>
In Myanmar, about 75 percent of the total population resides in
rural areas and the majority of the rural people mainly rely on
agriculture for their living.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture accounts for 36 percent of the country's gross
domestic product and 35 percent of the total export earnings and
provides 63 percent of employment.
</P>
<P>
The CIRDAP, established in 1979 and based in Dhaka, capital of
Bangladesh, is aimed at eradicating poverty in rural areas,
creating new job opportunities and enhancing economy and living
standard.
</P>
<P>
CIRDAP member countries have a total population of 1.5 billion,
the majority of whom lives in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar became in 1995 the 12th member of the CIRDAP, which
also groups Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Fiji, India, Indonesia, Iran,
Japan, Laos, Malaysia, Nepal, Pakistan, the Philippines, Sri
Lanka, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
