<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Foreign Trade Gap Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh registered an external
trade deficit of 2.694 billion U.S. dollars in the 1998-99 fiscal
year, 14.5 percent higher than the previous fiscal year, The
Financial Express reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Bangladesh Bank's annual report for 1998-99, the
newspaper said the deteriorating balance of payment in the
external trade last year was principally due to the devastating
flood sweeping the country from July to September 1998 and the
subsequent huge import of food grains.
</P>
<P>
The export earning of Bangladesh in the 1998-99 fiscal year was
5.324 billion dollars, an increase of merely 2.9 percent over the
previous fiscal. The country enjoyed an export rise of 16.8
percent in fiscal 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The import expenditure in the 1998-99 fiscal was to the tune of
8.018 billion dollars, 6.6 percent higher than that of the
previous year. The country's import expenditure recorded an
increase of 5.1 percent in the 1996-97 financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
