<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Warns of Spread of HIV in Western Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Despite the low rate of HIV
infection in the western Pacific region, the World Health
Organization (WHO) warned of rapid spread of the virus if
intensive efforts are not undertaken in this part of the world.
</P>
<P>
The warning was given in a press release issued Wednesday by
WHO Regional Office for the Western Pacific, which called for more
attention to the rapid increase in heterosexual transmission of
HIV.
</P>
<P>
According to the Manila-based office, about 17 percent of
reported AIDS cases and 43 percent of reported HIV infections have
occurred in the 13 to 29 age group in this region.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the office noted, this year's World AIDS Day, which is
observed every December 1, calls for a world AIDS campaign with
children and young people.
</P>
<P>
A decade ago, the office said, HIV transmission was essentially
among men who have sex with men, but the mode of transmission
shifted to injecting drug users and now to heterosexual
transmission.
</P>
<P>
There are about 35 million new cases of sexually transmitted
infections each year in this region, among which chlamydial
infection, often asymptomatic, has reached epidemic levels.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, it is estimated, more than 1 million people
will be HIV-positive in the region.
</P>
<P>
Shigeru Omi, WHO regional director for the Western Pacific,
said half of all new HIV infections are among young people under
25 years of age.
</P>
<P>
"This is why we must ensure that preventive programs meet the
needs of young people," he added.
</P>
<P>
Omi said the WHO will continue to support member states in the
region in promoting education and services for the young.
</P>
<P>
"We will also enhance partnerships with young people, parents,
communities, leaders and decision-makers so that we can provide a
healthier and better future for our next generation," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
