<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM-Elect Outlines Agenda for New Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Incoming New Zealand Prime
Minister Helen Clark has sped up her Labor Party's coalition talks

with the Alliance, promising that the deal will be ready for
formal
signing by Monday, just nine days after the general election.
</P>
<P>
According to the provisional results of last Saturday's
election,
the Labor Party and its partner the Alliance won a combined total
of
63 seats in the 120-seat parliament, enough to form a coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
The final results of the election will come out after the
special
votes are counted by December 7. Usually the final count will not
change the overall situation too much because the preliminary
results
covered about 90 percent of all votes cast at the election.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party and the Alliance have virtually agreed on a 20-
strong cabinet, with four slots going to the latter. The caucus of

the Labor Party will select its 16 ministers next Tuesday, with
portfolios to be allocated the next day, according to the local
media
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Clark was quoted as saying the cabinet lineup will be announced

next Thursday and sworn in the following day. She hinted that all
cabinet ministers will sit together in the parliament, unlike the
separate blocs of the previous government.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking for a much more integrated appearance to the
cabinet than was achieved with the last coalition," she said.
</P>
<P>
According to Clark, the new cabinet will meet for the first
time
on December 13 and the parliament will resume on December 21 for
the
traditional speech from the throne and passage of tax-raise
legislation and a bill banning party-hopping by MPs.
</P>
<P>
On the negotiations she has held with Jim Anderton, leader of
the
Alliance, Clark said the two parties do not need to put much in
writing because their relationship is so "harmonious."
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party does not envisage a winner-takes-all approach
but
wants to proceed by consensus and to allow flexibility for
conflicting policy stances, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
