<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Sees WTO Talks as Healthy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE, United States, November 30 (Xinhua) -- George Yong-
Boon Yeo, Singapore's trade and industry minister, said Tuesday
that the on-going trade talks of the World Trade Organization (WTO)
would bring a better life to over two billion people in the former
centrally-planned economies and in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
"China's entry into the WTO is an expression of this hope," Yeo
said at the opening session of the WTO's third ministerial
conference here.
</P>
<P>
"In 10 to 20 years, the recently concluded negotiations between
China and the United States on China's accession will be seen as a
major historical turning point for China, for the Pacific (region)
and for the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a 10-point statement, the Singaporean minister also urged
developed countries to take into account the interests of
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
"In coming to an agreement, it is of paramount importance that
the interest of the developing countries should not be ignored."
</P>
<P>
Developing countries should not be pressured at the last moment
to accept an agreement that they did not help to put together, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Yeo believes that opening up the agricultural sector will mean
a lot for many developing countries. As for the others, greater
market access in labor intensive sectors will enable hundreds of
millions to pull themselves out from abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
The mission of the WTO conference in Seattle is supposed to be
to create a prospering global economy and to increase the flow of
goods and services around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
