<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica's Poas Volcano in Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The Volcanology and
Seismological Observatory of Costa Rica (Ovsicori) warned Tuesday
that there is a danger of further emissions of gases from the
volcano Poas, which is situated some 30 kilometers north of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
"Since September, Poas' volcanic activity has increased,"
volcanologist Vilma Barbosa told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The column of smoke and ashes emitted reached a height of two
kilometers, and its contaminating effect has been increased since
the dry season set in as from November and will continue until
next April.
</P>
<P>
Without the rainfall diluting the chemical concentration, the
dry season will aggravate the effects caused by the gases on both
vegetation and human beings, mainly on the respiratory system and
skin for human beings, she said.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that communities located to the southeast of
the volcano will be affected by sulfur fumes as a consequence of
the wind," said Barbosa, who is in charge of the volcano for
Ovsicori.
</P>
<P>
She said the volcano may continue to be highly active, but she
did not say anything about the possibility of a large eruption of
the volcano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
