<HEADLINE> Shanghai Reports Increased Air Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- China's leading industrial and
commercial city of Shanghai reports a rapid growth in air traffic
in the first 10 months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Airplanes landing and taking off from the city carried more
than 12.08 million passengers and 620,000 tons of cargo during the
period, up 5.76 percent and 33.21 percent respectively from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attribute the upward trend to increased air
service to cities overseas.
</P>
<P>
This year, some 10 new routes were opened, bringing to 300 the
number of air links with other Chinese and overseas cities.
</P>
<P>
Royal Dutch Airlines, Britain's Virgin Atlantic Airways, and
Cargolux Airlines of Luxembourg all established air routes with
the city this year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is expecting an even greater growth in air traffic in
the future as Pudong International Airport began operations in
September, making Shanghai the only Chinese city with two
international airports.  
