<HEADLINE> Canadian, US Hostages Freed in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Seven Canadians and an American
kidnapped on the Ecuadorian-Colombian border 80 days ago were
released on Tuesday, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were released after a ransom of 3.5 million U.S.
dollars from the Canadian Embassy and the petroleum company, the
City Corp, was paid following negotiations with the kidnappers,
who agreed to cut the original demand of 20 million dollars of
ransom to the current amount, sources said.
</P>
<P>
After the payment was made, the hostages were released and then
taken to Quito where they were interviewed by local police before
they were allowed to return to their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
The Canadians were kidnapped on September 11 this year by a
guerrilla group during a trip in the Ecuadorian Amazon basin, with
three Spaniards, one American and a Belgian, but the identity of
the kidnappers still remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
The Spaniards and the Belgian were released two months ago
without ransom. 
