<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Bangladesh Opposition Vow to Oust Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Chiefs of the four parties of
the Bangladeshi opposition alliance finally sat together on
Tuesday evening vowing to "oust the government" and forming a
patriotic and strong government on a "broad-based unity."
</P>
<P>
"The combined effort of our four parties is to form a strong
patriotic government respectful to the constitution for facing the
challenges of the 21st century," said a joint declaration issued
after a much-talked-about summit, the first of the opposition
alliance since it was formed early this year.
</P>
<P>
Chairperson of the major opposition Bangladesh Nationalist
Party Khaleda Zia, Jatiya Party President H.M. Ershad and Golam
Azam and Azizul Haq, chiefs respectively of the Jamaat-e-Islami
and the Islami Oikya Jote (Islamic Solidarity Front), signed the
four-page declaration after the meeting of more than one hour.
</P>
<P>
Political observes here said the summit and the declaration
showed that the four parties have finally agreed on a same
platform in their joint movement to oust the government.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called upon all to form "all-party action
committees" in every locality, village, town and port across the
country for expediting the victory of the anti-government movement
and vowed to "collectively declare that the on-going movement will
get further momentum till the final victory."
</P>
<P>
It is obvious that the four parties have decided to launch
their future movement under a coalition leadership, by discarding
their previous separate campaigns to topple the government,
according to observes.
</P>
<P>
As the party chiefs pledged to form a strong patriotic
"broad-based unity," the observers believed that the four parties
must have reached consensus on whether to contest the next
parliamentary elections jointly or separately and on how to share
power if and after their movement is successful.
</P>
<P>
The declaration is equivalent to an election platform, as the
four leaders promised in it to repeal the Special Powers Act, give
autonomy to radio and television, curb terrorism and extortion,
establish economic uplift and modernize the defense, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
