<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Secret Graves Discovered in Northern Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican authorities
have discovered two secrete graves on the outskirts of Ciudad
Juarez, on the U.S. border, where the bodies of perhaps 100
victims of drug cartels may be exhumed.
</P>
<P>
At least 22 Americans are on the list of over 100 people who
have disappeared and may be discovered in the two graves, said
Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Around 200 police and military personnel from Mexico as well as
the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) and U.S. forensic
scientists were sent to Ciudad Juarez in the State of Chihuahua
Monday evening, 1,483 kilometers northeast of the Mexican capital.
</P>
<P>
The attorney general of the Mexican Republic (PGR) said in a
statement Tuesday that he had requested help from the FBI to
recuperate evidence and the remains of the Mexican and U.S.
victims on the outskirts of Ciudad Juarez.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican authorities believe that the bodies are victims of
the drug traffickers of the Juarez Cartel.
</P>
<P>
Over the last four years, and possibly longer, people have
disappeared from Ciudad Jaurez without a trace, including both
Mexican and U.S. citizens, said the statement from the PGR.
</P>
<P>
The ranches where the bodies have been found are called Campo
de Tiro and Paso del Norte, around 20 kilometers from Ciudad
Juarez.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, a witness being protected by the
FBI, who supposedly worked for the drug cartels and participated
in the murders, gave information leading to the discovery of the
clandestine graves.
</P>
<P>
So far 10 bodies have been exhumed, but it is unknown whether
the remains will be examined in Mexico or the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The north of Mexico, on the U.S. border, is one of the places
with the highest frequency of drug related activities, with
constant seizures of drugs by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
For years, Ciudad Juarez has been headquarters for the Juarez
Cartel, a drug gang formerly run by Amado Carrillo Fuentes .
Carrillo was the country's No. 1 cocaine trafficker before he died
in 1997 after plastic surgery. In the wake of his death, dozens of
people were killed in the city in what police believe was at least
in part a battle for control of the cartel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: East African Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The following is a
brief introduction of the East African Community formed on Tuesday
by Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
-- Partner states, Heads:
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Kenya, President Daniel arap Moi; The United
Republic of Tanzania, President Benjamin Mkapa; The Republic of
Uganda, President Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
 -- Geography:
</P>
<P>
 Total Area: 1.8 million Square kilometers. Position: facing
the Indian Ocean and across the equator; embracing Lake Victoria,
the largest freshwater lake in Africa, and Mount Kilimanjaro, the
highest mountain (5, 892 meters above sea level) in the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
-- Population:
</P>
<P>
About 80 million.
</P>
<P>
-- Language:
</P>
<P>
English, Kiswahili widely used in partner states.
</P>
<P>
-- History:
</P>
<P>
 All won independence from Western colonial rule in early
1960s. An East African Community was set up in 1967, but
collapsed in 1977 due to both internal and external factors which
were not supportive of regional integration at that time. They set
up a Permanent Tripartite Commission for East African Cooperation
on November 30,1993.
</P>
<P>
 The commission launched a secretariat at its headquarters in
Arusha, northern Tanzania on March 14,1996 to coordinate and boost
economic, political and social development.
</P>
<P>
 The three countries signed a treaty to re-establish the East
African Community on November 30,1999.
</P>
<P>
-- Objectives:
</P>
<P>
 The new EAC will expand and deepen economic, political and
social cooperation among the partner states for their mutual
benefit at a higher level. It will set up a Customs Union as the
entry point of the community, followed by a Common Market,
subsequently a Monetary Union and ultimately a Political
Federation of the East African States.
</P>
<P>
 -- Organizations under EAC:
</P>
<P>
The Summit of Heads of State, the Council of Ministers, the
 Coordination Committee, the Sectoral Committees, the East African
Court of Justice, the East African Legislative Assembly and the
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
-- Headquarters:
</P>
<P>
In the Arusha International Conference Center, Arusha,
northern Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
