<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to End Beef-On-Bone Ban Before Christmas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Tuesday it was
to lift its ban on beef-on-bone, hoping the move would convince
France and Germany to lift their embargoes on imports of British
beef.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the House of Commons, Agriculture Minister Nick
Brown said the decision was made following the advice of the chief
medical officers in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Brown said he aimed to have the nationwide ban lifted in time
to put cuts of meat such as T-bone steak back on menus in time for
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
"This lifting of the ban has been long awaited and I'm
delighted it can go ahead," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the product would be on sale again from 17
December.
</P>
<P>
Although the ban will be lifted on sales direct to consumers
and restaurants the ban on the use of some bone products in
processed food will remain in place.
</P>
<P>
Brown said the end of the ban would be a "welcome boost to the
beef industry in what continue to be difficult times."
</P>
<P>
The announcement came the day after the government's medical
advisers in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland met to study a
final academic report from Oxford University on the risk of
contracting BSE, or "mad cow disease", from beef bones.
</P>
<P>
Lifting the restriction is expected to boost Britain's efforts
to persuade France and other countries to lift their domestic bans
on British beef.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair will on Wednesday hold a "beef summit
" at Downing Street to devise a strategy to promote British beef
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the world's leading expert on assessing the risk of
BSE said the ban should be lifted immediately.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
