<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hands Over Last Military Base to Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Army Tuesday
handed over their last military base on the banks of the Panama
Canal to the Panamanian authorities after more than a century of
military presence in the Central American country.
</P>
<P>
The Fort Clayton Base had for over 80 years been the
headquarters of the South Command of the North American military
for its operations in Southern and Central America.
</P>
<P>
During an emotional civic ceremony, Edward Schuman, the
commander of the South Command, handed over the symbolic key to
the Panama Canal to Panamanian President Mireya Moscoso.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Schuman said that although the canal has been
handed back to Panama, its protection will still be one of the
priorities of the U.S. military authorities.
</P>
<P>
However, Mireya Moscoso said that U.S. military personnel would
never again be allowed to enter Panamanian soil.
</P>
<P>
Moscoso also denied that her government was at present holding
secret negotiations with the United States to prolong their
presence in Panama under the pretext of continuing the fight
against the drug traffickers and the threat from the Colombian
guerrilla movement.
</P>
<P>
By 1979 the U.S. had handed over a total of 13 military bases,
including the Howard air base, where the U.S. military were tying
to establish a Multi-Lateral Anti-Drugs Center (CMA) during the
Balladered government.
</P>
<P>
The Fort Clayton Base is the last of 14 bases to be handed over
to Panama since 1979 under the 1977 Panama Canal treaty signed by
U.S. President Jimmy Carter and the then Panamanian strongman Omar
Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
Only about 300 U.S. military personnel remain in Panama, and
they will gradually leave by the time of the final handover of the
canal at midday on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
Panama plans to use 325 acres for a "Knowledge City" complex of
schools and research institutions.
</P>
<P>
The first U.S. soldiers permanently assigned to Panama arrived
in 1911 to guard construction efforts of the Panama Canal, which
was opened in 1914.
</P>
<P>
Until the mid-1990s, more than 10,000 U.S. troops had been
based in Panama. At the height of the U.S. presence, during World
War II, about 65,000 U.S. troops were based in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
