<HEADLINE> Italian Premier to Visit Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema
is scheduled to arrive in Tripoli Wednesday to become the first
Western head of government to visit Libya in years and seal
sharply improved bilateral relations which have ensured for Italy
an avant-garde role in Libyan ties with Europe and the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
Italian news agency Ansa reported Tuesday that some diplomatic
sources affirmed that D'Alema's arrival will mark another decisive
step in returning Libya to the international community.
</P>
<P>
In this connection, they recalled the process begun in the
spring when Libyan leader Muammar Gheddafi turned over to the
Netherlands two countrymen suspected in the bombing of a Pan Am
flight over Lockerbie which killed all 270 people aboard, thus
ending a decade of United Nations sanctions against his nation.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the Italian premier's visit began in the
summer when, in early August, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini paid his second visit to Libya in four months to continue
Italy's leadership in easing its troubled North African neighbor
back toward what diplomats call "normalization" with the rest of
the world.
</P>
<P>
At the same point, a 5.5 billion U.S. dollars deal was signed
by the Italian petrochemicals group Eni and the Libyan state oil
company NOC to extract gas in Libya and pipe it to Italy's south
island of Sicily, an accord described at the time as the clearest
recent sign that the two nations intended to continue making
bilateral relations both warmer and more profitable.
</P>
<P>
One of the leading items was intended to totally end problems
linked to Italy's colonial past in the country, from 1911 until
the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
In this connection, Italy agreed to carry out any mine clearing
operation which might be needed.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema will reach Tripoli in Wednesday afternoon for a meeting
with Prime Minister Muhammad Abhad al-Manqush.
</P>
<P>
As is customary, the Italian premier's encounter with Gheddafi
will not be confirmed until the last minute for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Certain to come under review is Italy's status as Libya's
leading trading partner, and accounts for 20.3 percent of exports
sent to the country and takes up 41.3 percent of Libyan exports.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the value of this trade was reported at 5.515 trillion
lire (about 3 billion U.S. dollars) in Libyan exports to Italy and
1.727 trillion (about 0.9 billion U.S. dollars) in Italian exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
