<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall Broadly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell
broadly Tuesday in fears about the U.S. runaway economic growth
and on profit-taking as well.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 70.11 at 10,877.
81, expanding its loss of 40.99 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index fell 18.92 at 1,388.91 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 85.21 or 2.4 percent at 3,336.16.
</P>
<P>
Investors shed blue chip stocks to finish with a loss
obviously in fears about unchecked consumer spending which will
fuel the hot economic growth. The index rose as mush as 97 points
during the trading.
</P>
<P>
Recent Report of a booming start to the holiday shopping
season have convinced some investors that consumer spending
remains unchecked despite three interest rate hikes this year in
an effort by the Federal Reserve to cool off the U.S. economy.
The worries were fueled by a Conference Board report that consumer
confidence rose sharply in November after a four monthly declines.
</P>
<P>
Profit-taking also dragged the market lower. Investors sold
technology stocks to lock in profits from their stunning run in
the past few weeks. The Nasdaq index rose 12.1 percent for the
month of November and 56 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 5.32 at 631.18 and the Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies fell 2.87 at 454.08. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 0.69 at 832.81.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,618 up, 1,531 down and 442
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 946.86 million shares from 863.90
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
