<HEADLINE> Riot Police Clash with WTO Demonstrators in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Riot police clashed with anti-
capitalist demonstrators hurling bottles, cans and sticks in
central London on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
A transport police van was overturned and set on fire by
demonstrators and several people were injured.
</P>
<P>
The violence broke out after approximately 1,000 people
gathered outside Euston railway station for a rally.
</P>
<P>
Around 500 protesters, some of them wearing masks, broke away
from the main demonstration and surged towards police.
</P>
<P>
Officers, some with riot shields, closed a section of Euston
road and surrounded the station.
</P>
<P>
A sizable police presence was blocking their way into the rail
terminal and attempting to keep the demonstrators within a
controlled area at the station.
</P>
<P>
But some protesters were attempting to break through the police
lines into Euston Road.
</P>
<P>
The trouble followed a day of peaceful protests in London.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said at least three people were arrested and
several bystanders were injured when the anarchists hurled bottles,
iron bars, paving stones and other debris as police moved forward
to push them back from the station entrance.
</P>
<P>
A similar protest on June 18 turned into London's most violent
for a decade as protesters burned cars, smashed offices and
battled with riot police.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's protest was, until the Euston Station outbreak, more
restrained at areas in London's City financial district and at the
headquarters of Citibank in Lewisham, south London.
</P>
<P>
But at about 7 p.m. protesters brandishing placards saying "
Kill Capitalism" and "WTO equals World Thieves Organisation"
started ripping up paving stones and guard rails just outside the
station on a small grass forecourt.
</P>
<P>
The protesters also voiced opposition to the privatization of
Britain's railway systems. "Privatization Kills, Capitalism Kills",
said another placard. 
</P>
