<HEADLINE> EU Waits For France Response on Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Tuesday that it is still waiting for French response to the
commission's initial legal steps against it despite its failure to
report about the timetable of lifting the ban on British beef.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU)'s executive branch had not yet received
France's response to a letter it sent two weeks ago asking the
French government to justify its failure to lift the ban. The
deadline for such a reply was set on November 30.
</P>
<P>
But a commission spokesman said the EU executive will not press
ahead with the next step in its legal action for the moment
because the beef dispute seems increasingly likely to be resolved
diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
"We're expecting the reply very soon, presumably after the
French food agency meets later this week," Luc Veron, the
spokesman told a news briefing at the EU executive's headquarters
in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"Things are apparently going rather smoothly...This is not on
the agenda for tomorrow's Commission meeting, which is already an
indication that we do not intend to take any step tomorrow," Veron
added.
</P>
<P>
Under EU legal procedures, France should respond by November 30
to the Commission's request. The next step could be a so-called "
reasoned opinion" through a letter before taking France to court.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the French government has indicated that the ban
could be lifted as early as this week, after intensive diplomatic
contacts between Britain, France and the EU executive.
</P>
<P>
British beef exports were banned in March 1996 because of fears
that the so-called mad cow disease would spread brain disease in
humans. But France keeps the ban despite the all-clear from the EU
and the EU commission started to take the legal action two weeks
ago to force it to overturn the embargo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
