<HEADLINE> African Decade of the Disabled Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The African Decade of Disabled
People was launched in Ghana's capital Accra on Tuesday, calling
on governments to do more to improve the quality of life of the
disabled on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The decade, which begins from the year 2000 to 2009, is being
launched under the auspices of the Pan African Federation of the
Disabled (PAFOD) as part of the International Day of the Disabled
which falls on December 3, the Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Charles Appiagyei, president of the Physically Disabled of
Ghana, performed the launch.
</P>
<P>
By and large, the United Nations Decade of the Disabled has a
global approach to the problems of disability and the solutions
offered were general and global, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is therefore the need for a decade of disabled people
in Africa which would have an African approach to the problems of
disability and thus develop African solutions to the problems,"
Appiagyei said.
</P>
<P>
He said wars and other forms of violence, poverty and
epidemics are among some of the reasons for the increasing
incidence of disability on the continent. 
</P>
