<HEADLINE> Graham: Do Away with Don </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Tottenham Hotspur manager
George Graham reckons that refereeing standards in Europe are much
better than the top echelon in England and that Premiership
referees' officer Philip Don should be made redundant.
</P>
<P>
Graham was furious with Paul Alcock's handling of Spurs' game
at Newcastle on Sunday when six Tottenham players were booked. He
called the Surrey official - the man infamously pushed over last
season by Italian star Paolo di Canio - "the worst I've seen this
season."
</P>
<P>
But the outspoken Scot now admits: "I don't blame him (Alcock) -
not entirely, anyway. I blame the system in which referees have to
operate."
</P>
<P>
He continued: "They are too worried about having to do things
to please assessor in the stand. It is like Big Brother watching
them.
</P>
<P>
"Premiership referees have had their sense of responsibility
and ability to use common-sense taken away from them. I honestly
feel sorry for them because, to be a referee, they must love the
game but now they are officiating with fear.
</P>
<P>
"They seem to feel they have to do everything to the letter of
the law or they will get low marks from the assessor and will be
taken off the Premiership list.
</P>
<P>
"This has to change and the first thing I would do is dispose
of the role of referees' officer.
</P>
<P>
"The appointment of Philip Don was supposed to improve
relations between clubs and referees, but I am afraid it is not
working. I cannot see what good he has done."
</P>
<P>
Former FIFA referee Don is currently in Milan assisting with
the world governing body's experiments to test of feasibility of
having two referees on duty in top matches. A recent dry-run of
the idea in a friendly match in Italy had to be abandoned after
crowd trouble saw the game called off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
