<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Progress in Debt-to-Equity Swap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Four creditors led by China's
State Development Bank (SDB) signed a debt-to-equity swap
agreement today with Weihe Chemical Fertilizer Plant from Shaanxi
Province in northwest China. The debt-to-equity agreement is worth
some 2.052 billion yuan (247 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the SDB will convert 1.267 billion yuan of
its credit to equity while the three asset management companies of
Cinda, Huarong and Great Wall will convert 601 million yuan, 111
million yuan and 73 million yuan respectively.
</P>
<P>
The fertilizer plant was completed in May this year and funded
by Japanese government loans and domestic complementary investment.
Heavy debts means that the plant will not be able to make profits.
</P>
<P>
After the implementation of the debt-to-equity swap, the asset
to liability rate of the enterprise will be lowered from 103
percent to 58 percent. The plant is expected to become profitable
soon after the swap.
</P>
<P>
Being China's largest policy-oriented bank, the SDB has so far
signed debt-to-equity swap agreements with 18 enterprises
involving total debts of some 20 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
