<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt-Equity Conversion Proceeding Well With Major Chinese Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The debt-equity conversion job
of the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC) has been
going well in the last two months, a top bank official said in
Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Jianqing, ICBC's vice-president, said that his bank has
established debt-equity conversion organizations both in the
headquarters and local branches, with risk management, planning
and loan management staff.
</P>
<P>
The bank has also formed a standard working procedure in debt-
equity conversion with officials at different levels undertaking
clearly defined responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The ICBC has organized working conferences at different levels
so that its officials will be familiar with the government's debt-
equity conversion policy.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that many state-owned enterprises (SOEs) have been
losing money because they have carried out major technical
upgrading projects with bank loans or relied on bank loans to
start their businesses. These loans have turned into heavy debts
and reduced profitability. Converting their bank debts into
equities held by the bank asset management companies would
remarkably lower their debt level and financial costs.
</P>
<P>
For example, the first 42 enterprises recommended to ICBC had
an average debt asset ratio of over 60 percent in 1998. It is
estimated that this figure would drop by 9.5 percentage points
after the debt-equity conversion practice.
</P>
<P>
Jiang further pointed out that the 42 firms recorded a loss of
1.04 billion yuan in 1998, while their interest rate payment would
decrease by 1.78 billion yuan after the debt-equity conversion.
Debt-equity conversion would get rid of bad assets and thus
improve asset quality, profitability and also reduce operation
risks of banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
