<HEADLINE> Savimbi Can't Go Abroad: Ex-rebel Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A repentant ex-chief of the
rebel UNITA security department has said that Jonas Savimbi can't
go abroad if he still wants to keep his military strength and
safeguard his forest regime.
</P>
<P>
"If he goes abroad, his troops and followers will immediately
surrender," said Anacleto Chingufo, chief of the department of
security of the National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) from 1991 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
As for the whereabouts of the UNITA rebel leader, Chingufo said
that Savimbi should be somewhere between Andulo and the River
Kwanza.
</P>
<P>
Chingufo also said that at this moment, Savimbi has few cadres,
and those young people following him to the forest areas have
realized that the war is inglorious.
</P>
<P>
"They didn't come here (to surrender) just because they can't
flee away from the control of the security forces of the UNITA,"
the Angolan media Wednesday quoted Chingufo as saying.
</P>
<P>
After a 38-day general offensive against the rebels in the
central highland starting from mid-September, Savimbi and his
followers have been driven into mountainous areas. Although the
Angolan government said that it has known the trace of the rebel
leader, Savimbi disappeared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
