<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Vietnam Makes Progress in Ensuring Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- After over a decade of pursuing
the economic renovation and open-up policy, Vietnam has been able
to maintain a stable growth in agricultural production,
particularly in food production, while making progress in ensuring
food security.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam used to suffer from chronic grain shortage. In 1987,
the country's total grain yield was only 17.5 million tons. In
March 1988, there were 9.3 million of people in 21 provinces in
the north suffering from serious shortage of food. The Vietnamese
government had to import more than 700,000 tons of grain that
year.
</P>
<P>
There had been a great improvement in the country's grain
production in 1988, when Vietnam's total grain output reached
19.58 million tons, over 2 million tons higher than that of 1987.
</P>
<P>
The average yearly growth rate of Vietnam's total grain output
increased by 5.6 percent from 1988 to 1997. Vietnam's total grain
yields were 31.3 million tons last year and 33.8 million tons this
year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam began exporting rice in 1989. On the average, it
exported more than 1.7 million tons annually from 1989 to 1998. In
1998, Vietnam became the world's second biggest exporter of rice
with more than 3.8 million tons shipped abroad. Vietnam will
export 4.4 million to 4.5 million tons of rice this year.
</P>
<P>
The development of Vietnam's food production has contributed
greatly to the stabilization of the country's socio-economic
situation and the improvement of the living conditions in the
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese people had only 267 kilos of grain per capita in
1980 and 332 kilos per capita in 1989. In 1998, Vietnamese people
enjoyed more than 400 kilos of grain per capita.
</P>
<P>
However, Vietnam is still not safe from famine. According to
reports from different areas in the country, in early 1999, as
many as 2.3 million people in 34 cities and provinces were still
suffering from chronic hunger.
</P>
<P>
Hence, the threat of famine still remains a scourge, haunting
many communities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government now considers food security as one of
top priorities in the process of industrialization and
modernization.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has launched a movement for reducing poverty and
eradicating hunger, under which hunger will be basically
eradicated in the country in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
