<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation in November Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's national inflation
in November rose to 0.25 percent from 0.06 percent in October,
National Bureau of Statistic (BPS) announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of BPS Sugito Suwito said the increase of inflation
was triggered by the rise of consumer price index, particularly
food commodities.
</P>
<P>
"Inflation in November is higher than October. Food commodities
such as meal and eggs are the largest contributors for November
inflation. Generally food commodities suffered an inflation of
1.17 percent in November," Suwito said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
But he also said some commodities such as rice, cooking oil,
vegetables, fruit and gold declined.
</P>
<P>
"The descent of these commodities has held inflation level in
November not to be higher than 0.25 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that inflation growth for 1999 calendar year
(January to November) was 0.27 percent, while for the 1999/2000
fiscal year (ending at March 31) inflation was recorded minus 3.68
percent.
</P>
<P>
BPS reported that year to year inflation was 1.58 percent or
sharply declined from 78.31 percent in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
"The increasing of food commodities price is also supported by
the upcoming fasting month due to fall in the second week of
December," Sugito said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
