<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's External Debt Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's total foreign
debt commitment at the end of September stood at 7.8 billion U.S.
dollars, 3.2 percent lower than the 8.06 billion dollars a year
earlier, according to the central bank of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The latest edition of the Bank of Tanzania monthly economic
review indicates that the amount also represents a fall of 3.3
percent compared with 8.07 billion dollars in debt commitment at
the end of August.
</P>
<P>
Disbursed outstanding debt stood at 6.51 billion dollars, while
 committed undisbursed debt had reached 1.29 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Multilateral debts accounted for 53.7 percent and bilateral
debt about 38.8 percent of disbursed outstanding debt, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Treasury remained the largest
borrower, accounting for as much as 93.2 percent of the disbursed
outstanding debt.
</P>
<P>
No new loans were contracted and no disbursements were made in
the month under review, while actual debt service amounted to 15.7
million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
