<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Police Raids Religious Group For Alleged Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Japanese police raided on
Wednesday the facilities of a religious organization suspected of
swindling billions of yen from its followers.
</P>
<P>
The searches in nine prefectures hit 74 of Ho-no-Hana
Sampogyo's facilities, including the organization's head office in
Fuji, Shizuoka Prefecture, and its offices in Tokyo's Shibuya Ward,
police sources said.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest search conducted on a religious group in
Japan since April 1995, when investigators raided 120 facilities
of Aum Shinrikyo in 27 prefectures.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, 1,100 people have filed suits against Ho-no-Hana
Sampogyo and its leader Hogen Fukunaga in 10 district courts,
seeking a total of 5.5 billion yen (about 54 million dollars) in
compensation.
</P>
<P>
Fukunaga and other leaders of the religious group are suspected
of falsely diagnosing serious ailments such as cancer based on
inspections of the soles of people's feet and of claiming that
payments of millions of yen would cure the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
Police based Wednesday's searches on allegations that Fukunaga
and other senior group members cheated three housewives out of 22
million yen (215,000 dollars) from November 1994 to June 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, the senior members of the group told
the alleged victims that their family members would suffer from
cancer unless they underwent expensive five-day training sessions
at the group's Fuji headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The suspects defrauded some followers out of several million
yen each by selling hanging scrolls, ornaments and other goods,
after warning the followers that they will die young, or their
company will go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said the group has collected about 61 billion
yen (595 million dollars) from its 30,000 followers.
</P>
<P>
The group, founded by Fukunaga in around 1980, was recognized
in 1987 as a religious group eligible for preferential tax
treatment by the prefectural government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Govt Proposes Legislative Amendments to Counter Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government
plans to propose a number of amendments to two ordinances to
further enhance the effectiveness of the confiscation and anti-
money laundering provisions.
</P>
<P>
The Drug Trafficking (Recovery of Proceeds) Ordinance (DTRPO)
and Organized and Serious Crimes Ordinance (OSCO) provide for,
among others, the tracing, restraining and confiscation of
proceeds derived from drug trafficking, organized crimes or
specified offenses as well as the criminalization of dealing with
the proceeds of drug trafficking and other indictable offenses.
</P>
<P>
To adequately reflect the gravity of the money laundering
offense, it is proposed that a person who commits an offense under
this new section should be liable on conviction upon indictment to
a fine of 1 million HK dollars (128,000 U.S. dollars) and to
imprisonment for five years, or on summary conviction to a fine of
250,000 HK dollars (32,000 U.S. dollars) and to imprisonment for
two years.
</P>
<P>
To deter people from dealing with property known or believed to
represent proceeds of a drug trafficking, or indictable offense,
and to reflect the gravity of the offense, it is proposed that the
maximum term of imprisonment be increased from 14 years to 20
years.
</P>
<P>
Proposed amendments also include, among others, a penal
provision to deter people from knowingly deal in any realizable
property in contravention of a restraint or charging order.
</P>
<P>
A Drug Trafficking and Organized Crimes (Amendment) Bill 1999,
which has included the proposed amendments, will be gazetted on
December 3, and tabled at the Legislative Council for First
Reading and Second Reading debate on December 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
