<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Arabica Coffee Output to Rise by 2,500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 1 (Xinhua) - Production of arabica
coffee in Tanzania is expected to increase by 2,500 tons to 48,500
this season from last year's 46,000 tons, the Tanzania Coffee
Board said.
</P>
<P>
The coffee board attributed the possible increase to Tanzanian
government's efforts to revive the crop in areas where production
was affected by El Nino rains last year and the acreage expanded
by investors, the Financial Times reported Wednesday..
</P>
<P>
For the past three years the coffee sector including the coffee
board, cooperative societies and private companies devoted
considerable energy to improving the crop in the peasant or
household level.
</P>
<P>
Among strategies employed to revive the crop include
establishing coffee plots and distributing seedlings to farmers as
well as assuring farmers on price trends and how to solve other
problems, said the coffee board.
</P>
<P>
Coffee has been the major export in Tanzania's foreign trade
for the past two or three decades with an annual earning of 400
million U.S. dollars through a direct export of over 100,000 tons
of green coffee per year.
</P>
<P>
Coffee production has slumped in recent years because of bad
weather conditions and mostly, economic factors.
</P>
<P>
Despite that, the crop still stands as the leading single
export crop in Tanzania, no doubt due to its quality and quantity
amid some of the biggest, most competitive world markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
