<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Export Rises, Import Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 1 (Xinhua)-- The value of Indonesia's export
has slightly risen in October to 4.587 million U.S. dollars or
2.13 percent higher than September, the National Bureau of
Statistic (BPS) reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But it said that from January to October, the country's export
value was 39.625 million dollars or down 3.53 percent compared
with that of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
"The descent of the country's export value was triggered by the
fall of non-oil and gas export value," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Non-oil and gas export value in October was 3.541 million
dollars or suffered a descent of 1.1 percent compared the previous
month, while cumulative export value from January to October went
down to 7.12 percent compared to the same period of 1998," it
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chairman of BPS Sugito Suwito said the country's
import value in October was 2.028 million dollars or lower than
September which reached 2.127 millions dollars.
</P>
<P>
Suwito said from January to October, import value reached to
19.742 million dollars or declined by 12.55 percent compared to
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
"But import of consumption goods from January to September rose
to 1.880 million dollars or 39.18 percent higher compared to the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the same time, he said the country's economy growth is
expected to grow by 0.12 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But the International Monetary Fund (IMF) predicted that
Indonesia's economy growth rate in 2000 will be two percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
