<HEADLINE> India, Vietnam Ink Four Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- India and Vietnam Wednesday
inked four agreements, which included a 600-million-Indian-rupee
(13.95 million U.S. dollars) credit to Vietnam on concessional
terms and the setting up of two software development and training
centres in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh city.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed by Indian and Vietnamese senior
officials in the presence of visiting Vietnamese President Tran
Duc Luong and Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to exchange instruments of
ratification of the Bilateral Investment Promotion and Protection
Agreement, which was signed during the visit of the Vietnamese
premier to India in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Another agreement between the foreign service institutes of the
two countries was to enhance exchanges of students, professors,
experts and reserach scholars.
</P>
<P>
The vietnamese president, who arrived here Wednesday for a
five-day state visit, said that Vietnam was interested in Indian
technology and industrial products.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed a desire to enter into long-term cooperation
with New Delhi in defence, trade and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
This is the first Vietnamese presidential visit to India since
late Vietnamese leader Ho Chi Minh's historic trip to India in
1958. 
</P>
</TEXT>
