<HEADLINE> ADB to Provide Bangladesh with Loan of 157m U.S. dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
is processing a loan of 157 million U.S. dollars for the proposed
Dhaka Power System Upgrade Project to make the city
self-sustainable in power, an ADB official said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The loan negotiations for the project have been completed and
are due for consideration by the ADB's board of directors later
this month, Khalid I. Rahman, manager of the Energy Division
(West) of the ADB, said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
There would be no crisis of power in Dhaka after 2005 if the
project is implemented, said Rahman, who led a mission of the
ADB's power sector at a donor coordination meeting held here on
November 28-30.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka has a high system loss of 25 percent, which needs to be
corrected for making the power sector financially viable, he said.
He stressed the need for improving efficiency and ensuring good
administration to achieve the target of reducing the system loss
to 18 percent by 2003.
</P>
<P>
The ADB has provided assistance to generation, transmission,
and distribution projects in Bangladesh, but its main focus has
been the Dhaka area where 40 percent of the country's electricity
is consumed, according to Rahman.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is one of the largest development partners of
Bangladesh's energy sector, which has so far received 1,070
million dollars in loans and 13 million dollars in technical
assistance grants from the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
