<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Demise of Planned Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- It was common under China'
s planned economic system that every work unit, or "danwei" in
Chinese pronunciation, had to build residential buildings for its
staff.
</P>
<P>
Tens of millions of government-subsided residential buildings
emerged in the last 50 years, each belonged to a certain "danwei",
which might be a government department, a factory, a hospital or a
school.
</P>
<P>
Under the planned economy, a "danwei" consisted of two parts:
the work area, and the staff's living quarters as welfare
facilities.
</P>
<P>
"These living quarters provide almost everything for its staff
members, including housing and dormitories, eateries,
kindergartens and department stores," said Li Shuqin, a
sociologist with the Hebei Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
However, the "danwei" model, which usually cost a work unit
heavily every year for maintenance and service, is being shattered
as housing reform is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
The market economy has been transforming the landscape of big
cities as a growing number of commercial apartment blocks have
been built for ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has allowed the people to purchase
their residential quarters at a "charitable price".
</P>
<P>
"For the first time, Chinese citizens have the chance to own
their own homes," said Li.
</P>
<P>
This not only means that a president of a company or a minister
of a government department will no longer take care of housing for
his employees. It also helps the work units reduce their financial
burdens for maintaining the staff living quarters.
</P>
<P>
From this year, the government allows citizens who have already
bought the work unit apartments to resell them to anybody they
want. Reselling work unit apartments has reached feverish pitch
across the country.
</P>
<P>
In Hebei Province, north China, most citizens have sold the
houses to people from other units or cities and provinces at a
market price, instead of to their units at a government price.
</P>
<P>
On the day when the government announced the decision in
Beijing, more than 10,000 people applied for selling their work
unit apartments.
</P>
<P>
"We want to buy a newly-built commercial house as the old
apartment that belongs to our `danwei' has poor facilities," said
a middle aged man, who gave his first name as Cao.
</P>
<P>
Many young people who could not wait for their work unit to
assign them an apartment are eager to buy or rent "danwei"
apartments because they are relatively cheap.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yuxin, who works with Beijing Telecom, said that the
housing reform enables people to move around more freely. "If I
have money, I can choose where I live; And if I am unhappy with my
boss, I can resign without worrying about whether he will
confiscate my room".
</P>
<P>
However, some people have a mixed feeling about work unit
assigned housing.
</P>
<P>
"In my assigned apartment everything is cheap and looked after
by my work unit. And it is just several steps from my office. All
the neighbors know each other and often have happy gatherings,"
said Zhang Jun, a doctor at the Shijiazhuang No. 5 Hospital, who
moved to a new residential area this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the new apartment block everything is market-
oriented and more expensive. Every face is unfamiliar and he
usually feels lonely.
</P>
<P>
To most urban Chinese, to find a new home outside the work unit
is still a novel experience. Most people have to continue to live
in their work unit apartments for the moment until they get enough
to buy new houses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0256 </DOCNO>
