<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Succeeds Nyerere as New Burundi Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela was designated here on Wednesday as the
new facilitator of the Burundi peace process at a summit of the
leaders of the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Mandela succeeded the late facilitator Julius Nyerere to
provide political leadership on the tortuous peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, Tanzanian founding president, died of leukemia in a
London hospital on October 14 at the age of 77.
</P>
<P>
The regional leaders urged all the parties to the bloody
Burundi conflicts including the government to genuinely extend
maximum cooperation to Mandela so as to enable him accomplish his
mission.
</P>
<P>
They also underscored the importance of accelerating the
momentum of the negotiations until concluding a final peace
agreement that will ensure lasting peace, genuine democracy and
security for all.
</P>
<P>
The summit was attended by presidents of Uganda, Tanzania,
Kenya, South Africa and Burundi and prime ministers of Ethiopia
and Rwanda as well as foreign minister of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Also participating were the Secretary-General of the
Organization of African Unity Salim Ahmed Salim as well as the
representative of the UN Secretary-General Berhanu Dinka.
</P>
<P>
The summit decided to meet every three months to receive the
negotiations progress, reiterating its firm position that there is
no alternative to a negotiated settlement to the Burundi conflict.
</P>
<P>
A minute of silence was observed by all delegations in
recognition of the commendable dedication and selfless efforts
exerted by Nyerere in search for a permanent solution to the
Burundi conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The summit noted that the negotiations have reached an advanced
stage and substantial progress has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
It decided to maintain Arusha in northern Tanzania as the venue
of the peace negotiations and also to continue with the
negotiation infrastructure already in place so as to maintain the
gained momentum and make use of the experience already realized.
</P>
<P>
The summit also reviewed the political and security situation
in Burundi,
</P>
<P>
noting with regret that despite the efforts made at the
regional, continental and international levels, the political and
security situation has not improved significantly as fighting
continues unabated.
</P>
<P>
Since June of 1998, several rounds of talks have been taken
under the guidance of Nyerere in Arusha, gathering all the
warring faction leaders at the same table to seek long-lasting
peace.
</P>
<P>
However, the death of Nyerere has stalled the proposed peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
A tiny landlocked country in the Great Lakes Region, Burundi
was dragged into bloody conflicts since October 1993 when the
first free elected ethnic Hutu President Melchior Ndadaye was
assassinated by the ethnic Tutsi-dominated Army.
</P>
<P>
So far some 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have been
allegedly killed during the endless ethnic conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Countdown Starts for Russian Parliamentary Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, December 1 (Xinhua) -- With State Duma elections just 18
days away, campaigning is in full swing for Russian political
parties' bid to vie for more seats, if at all, in the next lower
house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Although more than 5,000 candidates will take part in the race,
only a fraction of them will make it to the 450-seat chamber that
is expected to impact the country's political landscape in the
first four years of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
As federal troops are in the middle of an offensive against
rebels in the breakaway republic of Chechnya, a campaign that
would be completed at the earliest in one month's time as
predicted by Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev Wednesday, only 447
seats will actually be contested.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, the Communist Party, Fatherland-All Russia
and the Yabloko bloc look set to clear the hurdle of 5 percent of
the votes and finish at the top three. The Unity movement, whose
standing keeps rising with the full backing of the Kremlin and
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, is also expected to grab some seats.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Our Home is Russia, Union of Right Causes and the
Zhirinovsky Union, a bloc grouping Alexander Zhirinovsky's Liberal
Democratic Party and two other smaller parties, may or may not
garner the 5 percent of votes necessary to enter the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
According to opinion polls, the Communists and Fatherland-All
Russia will collect 30 percent and 20 percent of the votes
respectively, which points to a new State Duma dominated by
leftist and centrist forces.
</P>
<P>
As the outcome of the Duma elections would dictate the future
of Russia and sway the results of next year's presidential race,
various political forces have intensified their efforts in
consolidating their positions or clutching an eleventh-hour turn
for the better.
</P>
<P>
The Kremlin establishment, with much at stake for its future
and that of the country, has all along maintained an active role
in steering the elections to its advantage, despite its technical
status as "an outsider."
</P>
<P>
It has mobilized the media and other leverages in a campaign
against Fatherland-All Russia, which is considered hostile to the
Kremlin and seen as the most probable winner in both the
parliamentary and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Fatherland-All Russia, which enjoyed a comfortable lead
initially, appeared to be losing ground in the face of fierce
assaults from the Kremlin. The bloc's leaders, former Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, have seen
their prestige dropping, especially in comparison with Putin's
skyrocketing approval rate amid the military actions against
Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
Despite the setback, observers say, Fatherland-All Russia's
chance of winning first or second place in the elections remains
unshakable.
</P>
<P>
Unity, a bloc hastily established, reportedly at the behest of
the Kremlin, is one of the measures designed to counter the
leftist and centrist forces.
</P>
<P>
To make up for Unity's "congenital defects," the Kremlin has
asked Putin, who is enjoying record approval rating among the
Russians, to throw his weight behind the movement to somewhat
improve its standing.
</P>
<P>
However, whether Unity would become a force that achieves
steeper ascent is far from clear.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the Communists seem to be reaping the benefits of
the struggle between the Kremlin and Fatherland-All Russia,
inching back toward the top in recent opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Yabloko group, long branding itself as "a
rightist opposition" to the ruling establishment, is expected to
win more votes after former Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin joined
its ranks.
</P>
<P>
By and large, as Russia is a country where the president
wields the most formidable powers, the ultimate "showdown" will
come next June when the Russians decide who will replace President
Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Some provisions of the Russian constitution, however, have
made the parliamentary elections a forerunner to the presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian basic law, the president cannot dissolve the
parliament in his final six months in office. This rids Yeltsin of
a vital card in dealing with the new State Duma.
</P>
<P>
If the leftist and centrist forces dominate the new lower
house of parliament as is widely predicted, the Kremlin's plan to
maintain Putin or any other person of its choice at the head of
the government and subsequently succeed Yeltsin would be thrown
into doubt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
