<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng, Peres Vow to Cement Sino-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEL AVIV, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Both China and Israel enjoy
great potential for development and the prospect for bilateral
cooperation is very bright, said visiting top Chinese legislator
Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress of China, made the remarks during a meeting
with Israeli Minister of Regional Cooperation and former prime
minister Shimon Peres Tuesday night, one day before he ended a
week-long official goodwill visit to Israel.
</P>
<P>
China and Israel have their own advantages in development and
China is willing to work together with Israel on the basis of
mutual respect and mutual benefit in order to further friendly
cooperation between the two countries, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li spoke highly of the great contribution Peres had made to the
development of Sino-Israeli friendship during his tenure of office
as Israel's prime minister and foreign minister. Peres is now
honorary chairman of the Council for Promotion of Israel-China
Relations.
</P>
<P>
Peres said that during his visits to China in 1993 and 1997, he
had been deeply impressed by the great achievements the Chinese
people have made in the last 50 years, including the stability of
the society and the vigor of the economy.
</P>
<P>
What impressed him the most, however, is the spirit of
dedication of the Chinese people, Peres said, adding that this
spirit is the very reason for the vast development taking place in
China during the last five decades.
</P>
<P>
Peres extended his congratulations on the signing on November
15 of the bilateral agreement between China and the United States
on China's accession to the World Trade Organization. China's
ultimate entry to the world's largest trade body will be a big
development in the global economy and trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of development, Peres said Israel has succeeded in
developing its economy by relying on science and technology amid
miserable natural environment. The agricultural production has
increased by 17 times in the last few years thanks to the
introduction and development of the green house technology, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The problem Israel faces now is not the lack of new
technology, but the necessity for the people to realize the
potential importance of the hi-tech, Peres said.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with Peres, Li said China also realizes that the only
solution to the development of agriculture is science and
technology. Although much progress has been made in agri-tech,
biology engineering and water-saving projects, China still has a
lot to do in developing science and technology, Li said.
</P>
<P>
In the last few years, China and Israel have engaged in
effective cooperation in the field of agriculture with some
projects having achieved very good results, Li said. He expressed
his hope that the two sides will further strengthen cooperation in
agriculture and hi-tech.
</P>
<P>
Li praised Peres for the great efforts he had made for the
advancement of the Middle East peace process. As a permanent
member of the U.N. Security Council and a country keeping friendly
ties with both Israel and its Arab neighbors, China has been
paying much attention to the peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
China is glad to see that positive signs have emerged in the
peace process in the last few months and sincerely hopes for an
early solution to the lasting Israeli-Arab conflicts for the
benefits of both the Israeli and the Arab people, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li left Israel Wednesday for Oman, the last leg of his ongoing
Afro-Asian tour, which has already taken him to Mauritius, South
Africa, Kenya and the Palestinian self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
