<HEADLINE> Estrada Cites Driving Forces for Economy in New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Wednesday stressed the need to strengthen agriculture,
science and technology and culture, which he said will be the
driving forces to propel the country into the mainstream of the
global economy in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Estrada emphasized the point in a speech delivered here at the
Rizal park Wednesday evening before switching on the 30-foot high
giant lantern, kicking off a series of activities welcoming the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said promoting the country's culture will enable
peoples everywhere in the world to see the real Philippine
picture, while science and technology will transform the nation's
industries for the benefit of the people.
</P>
<P>
But he said all these developments will depend on a successful
implementation of their agriculture programs, because the majority
of Filipinos, especially the disadvantaged sector in the rural
areas, are farmers.
</P>
<P>
"If we can unify and enhance these forces, the new millennium
will bring us more opportunities and prosperity," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
The coming of the new millennium, Estrada said, "should serve
as an inspiration to us Filipinos for these signals -- the
worldwide dawning of economic prosperity and hope with the
changing faces in business, commerce and technology."
</P>
<P>
"Here in our country, the new millennium means new challenges
for us to face the problems that come our way," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president was welcomed by a brass band upon his arrival at
the stage opposite the Rizal Monument, where he switched on the
giant lantern, dubbed Millennium Filipino.
</P>
<P>
The lantern, on top of which stands a countdown clock read as
the 31st day before the year 2000, marked the opening of the
Philippine celebration to welcome the coming of the new century
and the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Among those who were attending the ceremony were Senate
President Blas Ople, Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon, Manila
Mayor Joselito Atienza, as well as some foreign diplomats.
</P>
</TEXT>
