<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Attend First Gulf of Guinea Summit Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to attend the first
Gulf of Guinea Joint Commission (GGJC) summit in Sao Tome and
Principe in the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Dubem Onyia made
the announcement on Tuesday when he accompanied President of Sao
Tome and Principe, Miguel Travoada, to visit Ilorin in Kwara
State, the Guardian newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The GGJC was launched last month at a meeting in Gabon's
capital Libreville by presidents of the Republic of the Congo,
Equatorial Guinea, Gabon, Cameroon, Angola, Sao Tome and Principe
and Nigeria to strengthen dialog on regional conflicts and
security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Demarcation of economic zones and cooperation in the oil sector
are also on the agenda of the regional organization.
</P>
<P>
The sub-region is estimated to have around 14 percent of
world's offshore oil reserve.  
</P>
