<HEADLINE> Malaysia Y2K Ready in Critical Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is "in good shape
and Y2K ready" for critical sectors, confident of a trouble-free
rollover into the new year, Energy, Communication and Multimedia
Minister Leo Moggie said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Computer systems in all the sectors critical to the nation's
well-being are in an advanced state of readiness to take the new
year in their stride, he said in a statement issued here.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, there will be anxious eyes monitoring all the critical
sectors from our Y2K Control Center in Kuala Lumpur, but not with
the expectation of any major difficulties," he said.
</P>
<P>
The critical sectors identified by the Malaysian government
include energy, communications, water supply, banking, insurance
and capital market, transportation, health, oil and gas, sewerage
and government.
</P>
<P>
Each of the nine sectors has its own contingency plans that
have been tested and are in place, while an overall contingency
plan has been developed, looking at the state of preparedness from
a nationwide perspective and catering for the unlikely need to
manage and contain events to uphold public order and national
security, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Well before new year's eve, all the work will have been
completed, with tested contingency plans in place to deal with any
unexpected problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government, which recognized the need for decisive action
early, set aside 850 million ringgit (223.684 million U.S.
dollars) for solving Y2K problems while having agreed to provide
additional funding if it became necessary, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the sectors themselves would be
spending a further 1,100 million ringgit (263.157 million U.S.
dollars) to ensure Y2K preparedness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
