<HEADLINE> OIC Delegation to Visit Moscow Monday: Iranian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has announced that he would lead a delegation of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) to visit Moscow on
Monday to discuss the Chechen issue with Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi told a press conference Wednesday that his trip was
not aimed at mediation but fact-finding, and his delegation had no
plan on mediation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Islamic countries are concerned about the
situation in Chechnya, adding that the OIC and its current
chairman Iran feel a strong responsibility to employ any possible
means to stop war and bloodshed in the region.
</P>
<P>
Expressing satisfaction over the opportunity Russia has
provided for Iran and the OIC to discuss the Chechen issue, the
minister also hoped that by becoming further acquainted with the
facts in Chechnya, resolution could be found to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov informed Kharrazi on
Monday night that Russian cabinet had agreed to the proposal by
Kharrazi on a visit by an Iran-led Islamic delegation to Moscow
for talks on the Chechen issue.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet accepted the proposal in light of the friendly
relations between Iran and Russia and the fruitful negotiations
held in Tehran during my stay in Iran," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with Ivanov during his
one-day visit to Iran on Sunday, Kharrazi said that he proposed a
visit by an OIC delegation to Moscow and Ivanov promised to convey
the message to the Russian cabinet.
</P>
<P>
However, Ivanov stressed that the Chechen issue was an internal
affair of the Russian Federation, denying any attacks on and
massacre of civilians in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Before anything else it should be said that no such attacks
have been or can be made on Chechnya because the territory is part
of the Russian Federation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that Russia's military actions in Chechnya are not
against Muslims, rather terrorists, regardless of their
nationality or religious affiliation. 
