<HEADLINE> India Imposes Customs Duty on Two Wheat Varieties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government
Wednesday imposed a 50 percent customs duty on common and "dhurum"
varieties of wheat in a bid to stimulate the offtake of wheat from
the central pool.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha announced the imposition of the
duty, effective Wednesday, in a statement to parliament.
</P>
<P>
With the availability of relatively cheaper import, he said,
the offtake from the central pool had been low despite
liberalization done through the open market sale scheme.
</P>
<P>
Between May and November this year, almost 1.5 million tons of
wheat reached Indian ports. The landed cost of wheat was much
lower than the open sale rate fixed for the Food Corporation of
India. 
</P>
