<HEADLINE> Chinese Teenagers with HIV Virus on Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Teenagers with the HIV virus
account for at least 75 percent of the 5,000-plus carriers in
southwest China's Yunnan Province, the area with the most serious
incidence rate of the disease in the country.
</P>
<P>
The province kicked off a month-long poster design contest
today, which is World AIDS Day, aiming to increase AIDS awareness
among the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
International organizations, such as the Medecins sans
Frontiers (MSF), or Doctors Without Borders, have also become
involved in China's AIDS-prevention activities.
</P>
<P>
The number of reported HIV cases has grown steadily since 1989,
when the province first found HIV carriers among the drug addicts
in its western border area adjacent Myanmar, said local public
health officials.
</P>
<P>
And the situation has worsened since 1996. The disease has
spread from border areas to cities and towns, they said, adding
that unsafe sex has become another main cause.
</P>
<P>
The 5,104 HIV cases, and the 157 AIDS cases in the province by
1998 accounted for 44.3 percent and 57.3 percent respectively of
the country's total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
