<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Discuss Palestinian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on Wednesday held talks with visiting Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat on the latest developments of Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before leaving Cairo for Gaza, Arafat
said the talks focused on the dispute between the Palestinians and
Israel over Israeli troop withdrawal from another 5 percent of the
West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has proposed some changes for the maps of
withdrawal put forward by Israel, but Israel has failed to
respond, Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israel of trying to avoid giving a reply.
</P>
<P>
Prior to each of the previous withdrawals, the two sides would
give their own suggestions and demands, and sign the maps after
discussions, Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
But this time, Israel decided the areas itself without
consulting the Palestinians, he said, stressing that it is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm el-Sheikh Memo signed in September, the
withdrawal should take place on November 15. But the Palestinians
rejected the Israeli maps, saying the areas are too sparsely
populated and not contiguous.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Cairo on Tuesday after a visit to Moscow. He
met with Egyptian Prime Minister Atef Obeid Tuesday night on ways
of promoting bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Obeid said after the meeting that the two sides hoped to
increase their trade volume to 500 million U.S. dollars in the
coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
