<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five-Year Plan Enacted to Combat AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- In response to the 12th World
AIDS Day today, Changchun, capital of northeast China's Jilin
Province, announced its plan to curb AIDS in the coming five years
here at the first anti-AIDS working conference.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the city in northeast China will set up special
training courses at schools of all levels by the end of 2001,
aiming to increase AIDS awareness for more than 80 percent of the
local people.
</P>
<P>
In addition, establishment of some AIDS check-up labs in the
next two years will enable the city to control the disease through
a standardized network system by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Since the first case of AIDS carrier was detected in the
province in 1993 through the end of last year, 107 people in Jilin
have been confirmed as carrying AIDS HIV.
</P>
<P>
Among over 20 AIDS-infected people in Changchun, about 18 are
between the ages of 20 and 45, and the ratio of men and women with
AIDS HIV is 4:1, according to local health statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
