<HEADLINE> S.African Speaker Unveils Giant Red Ribbon to Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- South African National
Assembly speaker Frene Ginwala unveiled a giant red ribbon draped
across the Assembly building's entrance to mark World AIDS day on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ribbon is intended to highlight the necessity of a national
effort to combat AIDS and will remain draped for the whole of
World AIDS Week.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Ginwala said AIDS already affected
almost every family in South Africa in one way or another.
</P>
<P>
If the spread of the virus was not contained, the dreams of a
better life for all South Africans and their children would be
dashed, she said.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.6 million South Africans were HIV positive and 40
percent of all people going to hospital were HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
Ginwala called for more AIDS awareness, saying it had to be
everybody's concern.
</P>
<P>
The red ribbon was a symbol of both concern and hope for the
future, she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Western Cape African National Congress Women's
and Youth Leagues held a march in Cape Town on Wednesday to pledge
their support for the provincial government's anti-AIDS/HIV
programs. 
</P>
