<HEADLINE> Li Peng Arrives in Oman for Goodwill Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MUSCAT, December 1 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislator Li Peng
arrived here Wednesday on an official goodwill visit to Oman aimed
at boosting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the Standing Committee of China's National
People's Congress, is the first Chinese top legislator to visit
Oman since the two countries established bilateral ties in 1978.
</P>
<P>
He was greeted at the royal airport by Hamoud al-Harthy,
president of the state council of Oman, and other members of the
council.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit here, Li is expected to hold talks
with Hamoud al-Harthy and meet with Abdullah al-Qatabi, president
of the Consultative Assembly of Oman.
</P>
<P>
China-Oman relations developed smoothly during the past 21
years. In 1987 their foreign ministry officials launched an annual
consultative mechanism, and bilateral trade reached 746 million
U.S. dollars in 1998 as China became the fourth largest buyer of
Omani oil. That year China imported 5.8 million tons of oil from
the Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
Oman is the last leg of Li's six nation Asian-African tour
which he said is designed to "deepen understanding, enhance trust,
promote friendship and expand cooperation." The tour has taken him
to Mauritius, South Africa, Kenya, Palestine and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
