<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tougher Rules Urged in Canada for Use of Pesticides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Tougher rules are being urged in
Canada for better protection of children from exposure to
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
"There is definitely cause for concern" about lax pesticide
controls, according to the Ontario College of Family Physicians
and the Canadian Environmental Law Association (CELA).
</P>
<P>
A 80-page study by CELA is being submitted to the House of
Commons, pointing out that most of the promises made since 1994 to
tighten the rules have been broken.
</P>
<P>
The study warns of a link between pesticide exposure and
reproductive effects ranging from decreasing fertility to
increased risk of spontaneous abortion.
</P>
<P>
"There appears to be a higher risk for some childhood cancers
such as leukemia and brain tumors associated with prenatal and
early exposure to certain pesticides," says the study released
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The CELA study, which was conducted last year, demands that
some 40 of the 7,500 pesticides registered in the country be
banned because they contain severely toxic agents known as
carcinogens.
</P>
<P>
The study also called for revisions to the registration
process, improved inspection of the use of pesticides and more
public access to pesticide information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
