<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safety Should Be Top Priority in Production: Vice-Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- In a televised State Council
conference here today, Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo urged that
effective measures should be taken to prevent major accidents in
production.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to implementation of State Council directives on
production safety, accidents and the number of casualties across
China have dropped this year compared with last year's same period,
Wu said.
</P>
<P>
But since October, he noted, accidents resulting from personal
negligence and poor project quality have been on the rise, he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and the
State Council have always attached great importance to safety in
production, he said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier stressed that safety needs to be integrated
with production and efficiency. It is of vital importance to
balance safety with production, economic growth and people's
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
He outlined six tasks for the safety education:
</P>
<P>
-- Leading officials at all levels should respect safety in
production;
</P>
<P>
-- A nationwide check-up on safety in production will be
conducted beginning today;
</P>
<P>
-- Measures will be taken to prevent possible hidden dangers
caused by major accidents;
</P>
<P>
-- All accidents will be investigated and those who are mainly
responsible will be punished according to law;
</P>
<P>
-- A responsibility system will be instituted in all production
units; and
</P>
<P>
-- An educational campaign on safety in production will be
launched in all departments and areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
