<HEADLINE> Zambia Attracts $160 Million Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's foreign direct
investment inflows have reached an average of 160 million U.S.
dollars a year, placing it among the top seven sub-Saharan
countries in terms of attracting foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the United Nations Commission for Trade and Development
1999 world investment report, Standard Chartered Business Trends
November Issue available on Wednesday said Zambia had outperformed
Ghana and Uganda who are considered leaders of successful economic
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
Zambia is ranked along with Nigeria, South Africa, Angola,
Equatorial Guinea, Cote d'Ivoire and Zimbabwe as the top seven
sub-saharan economies in terms of attracting foreign direct
investment. 
</P>
