<DOCNO> XIE19991201.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Secretary Outlines Chances and Challenges for HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is out of recession
but still faces opportunities as well as challenges, Hong Kong
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a luncheon speech at a forum, Tsang said Hong Kong has
recorded a GDP growth for the first time since the final quarter
of 1997, and investment is starting to flow back as confidence
levels edge upward.
</P>
<P>
The government has revised upward its GDP estimate for 1999 to
a growth rate of 1.8 percent, instead of the earlier 0.5 percent,
based on the strong performance in the third quarter's GDP, Tsang
said.
</P>
<P>
"So, technically, we are out of recession", the finance
secretary proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
What enables Hong Kong to tide over the Asian financial crisis
is Hong Kong's long-standing policy of fiscal prudence, he said.
"By keeping the expenditure within the trend rate of growth over
time, we have built up sizable fiscal reserves," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Hong Kong has a shrinking revenue base,
partly as a result of the tax concession the government has made
over the years and partly as a result of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is facing a sizable deficit this year and the deficit
next year was forecast at some 5.6 billion HK dollars (717.9
million HK dollars), according to Tsang.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's tax base is shrinking, Tsang said, noting that in
the current fiscal year, around 70 percent of the yield from
salaries tax is being shouldered by 15 percent of salaries tax
payers, and the situation is similar for profit tax.
</P>
<P>
The government, which is expecting structural changes in the
revenue base, may no longer rely so much on land-related revenue,
as the land supply and demand stabilize, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to look at broadening our tax base to find other
stable sources of revenue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said it is his duty and the legislature's to bring Hong
Kong's financial position back into the black over the medium
term.
</P>
<P>
"This is also essential when if we are to maintain our
international credit rating, which underpins investors' confidence
in Hong Kong and the borrowing capability of local business,"
Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
Though Hong Kong's economic growth figures are encouraging,
Tsang said the region is still vulnerable to external factors,
most notably from Japan and the United States, where the interest
rate trend could still impact on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Another issue that needs to be addressed is Hong Kong's
long-term competitiveness, he said. "This will become even more
pronounced with the further opening up of the Mainland after its
accession into the WTO, a situation that will lead to increased
international competition in the nation's lower cost internal
markets."
</P>
<P>
Tsang warned that though Hong Kong may have the best services,
the best facilities, and the best expertise in brokering deals for
companies wanting to open up in China's mainland, if the costs are
high, Hong Kong "will be in danger of losing out to some other
regional cities."
</P>
<P>
He suggested that in some cases, Hong Kong's property prices,
rents and labor costs should have to be pegged back more if Hong
Kong is to provide real competition for its East Asian neighbors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
