<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: AIDS Virus Grips India's Urban Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Geeta's life changed two
years ago after her marriage with a bank clerk who had been
infected with the dreadful acquired immune deficiency syndrome
(AIDS).
</P>
<P>
Geeta, 28, a dweller in India's largest commercial city of
Numbai, had known the result when she went to a nearby hospital
for HIV test which, as she had expected, showed positive.
</P>
<P>
She is only one of millions of Indians infected by the fatal
human immune deficiency virus (HIV), which makes body's immune
system incapable of fighting diseases and infections.
</P>
<P>
While the government put the figures of HIV positive at 3.5
million, a report prepared jointly by the United Nations Program
on HIV/AIDS and the World Health Organization (WHO), said India is
home to about 4 million HIV-infected people, accounting for about
12 percent of the global burden of 33.6 million.
</P>
<P>
Even Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee admitted that AIDS has
become the most serious health problem the country is facing
today.
</P>
<P>
HIV has a significant grip on urban population in some southern
and western states of India with one pregnant women in 50 testing
positive for HIV, said the report entitled "AIDS epidemic updates:
December 1999."
</P>
<P>
HIV infection has also shot up in Northeastern parts of the
country, mainly through drug users who share the same syringe and
men who pass it to their wives.
</P>
<P>
What is more alarming is that 50 percent of those infected are
under the age of 24, said the National AIDS Control Organization
under the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion of the World AIDS Day Wednesday, Minister of
State for Health and Family Welfare N. T. Shanmugarm urged in a
newspaper report to educate people, especially the young, about
the ways and means to protest themselves and their dear ones from
this dreadful infection.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to all the people working on the AIDS control
program to work together, share knowledge and experience for the
control of HIV and AIDS before it is too late.
</P>
<P>
Having expanded and improved its surveillance system, India now
has a clearer idea of HIV prevalence, said the U.N. report
published here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, it stated, irrational fear and discrimination against
HIV positive patients have made prevention difficult in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Many hospitals reportedly turned away infected patients or
attended to them badly with many health workers felt that treating
HIV patients was a waste of time and money as they would
ultimately die.
</P>
<P>
Even worse, women, generally wives infected by their husbands,
were stigmatized and were frequently blamed by their in-laws for
the fate of their infected spouse, even in cases where they
themselves are not infected.
</P>
<P>
India witnessed 179,000 deaths due to AIDS last year out of the
total death toll of 2.285 million worldwide, according to WHO.
</P>
<P>
News media here complained that India, with a population of one
billion, has been extremely laggard in putting a proper system to
manage AIDS or HIV in place and the knee-jerk response of the
authorities and the general public to the disease has only
resulted in driving them underground. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
