<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Prepare Equipment for 500 Congo (K) Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Tuesday night asked U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
to make preparations to equip up to 500 U.N. military observers,
should a decision be taken to send such a mission to the war-torn
Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimously adopted resolution, the 15-member Council said
that the actual phased deployment of observers, together with
support and protection personnel, would be subject to another
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The Council stressed its intention to take such a decision
promptly on the basis of further recommendations by Annan ,taking
into account the findings of a U.N. technical team that has
visited the area.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. observer mission would help monitor a peace agreement,
signed in the Zambian capital of Lusaka in July to put an end to a
many-sided conflict in the central African country, formerly Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The observers might also serve as a forerunner of a U.N.
peacekeeping force of thousands of troops, though this is not
spelled out in the council resolution.
</P>
<P>
The fighting in Congo (K) pitted the government of President
Laurent Kabila, supported by Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola, against
rival rebel factions, backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. special envoy for Congo (K) is Kamel Morjane, who was
appointed by Annan earlier this month and has been Tunisia's
representative to the United Nations in Geneva since October 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
