<HEADLINE> Week-long Youth Festival Begins in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A week-long National Youth
Festival '99 marking the achievements and successes of the youth
development began in Bangladesh on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the festival in the capital city, Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina said the government would utilize the merit, vigor
and strength of the youths for making a prosperous nation to face
challenges of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
She said the government was determined to train the youths as
skilled forces capable of fighting poverty and unemployment so
that the nation could step into the next century as a
self-respected prosperous one.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting achievements of her government during the past
three and a half years, she said 900,000 unemployed youths were
imparted training, soft loans of nearly 2.3 billion taka (46
million U.S. dollars) were disbursed, and self-employment for
22,597 youth was created.
</P>
<P>
Youth training programs had been expanded from 230 centers to
470 centers since the Awami League took office in June 1996, she
said, urging the youths to rise above narrow political differences
and to devote themselves to nation-building tasks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on Tuesday, State Minister for
Youth and Sport Obaidul Kader said nearly 250,000 unemployed
youths each year were being given skill development training
through mobile programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
The overall youth development programs included skill
development training, motivation of the unemployed youths to
self-employment with credit, and poverty alleviation of the rural
landless and unemployed people, he said. 
</P>
