<HEADLINE> TD Bank Expects Bigger Income for Canadians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Toronto-Dominion Bank (TD Bank)
is expecting the standard of living in Canada to bounce back to
the level of late 1980s within a few years.
</P>
<P>
"We expect gains of between 1.5 and 2 percent per year in real
personal disposable income per person over the next few years --
the best performance since late 1980s," the Globe and Mail
newspaper Wednesday quoted a TD Bank senior economist as saying.
</P>
<P>
People living in Newfoundland, Ontario and Alberta will
experience the largest jumps in personal income, with Albertans
doing the best, according to the bank.
</P>
<P>
In the country's richest province of Ontario, surging exports
have added an extra 1 billion Canadian dollars (about 678 million
U.S. dollars) to the province's revenue this year.
</P>
<P>
Much of Canada's growth is considered benefiting from the
surging U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech boom that has made millionaires throughout
California's Silicon Valley has also spilled into Canada, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The latest example comes from Burnaby, British Columbia, where
45 employees at Siara Systems will share a windfall from a merger
deal between their U.S. parent company and another U.S.-based high-
tech firm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
