<HEADLINE> Reform Begins in China's University Logistics Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has started to reform
logistics services in its universities, aiming to set up a market-
oriented service network in three years that will satisfy the
needs of the higher education institutes in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The reform aims to relieve the present college administrations
of logistical responsibilities related to student services, and to
set up groups to provide the schools with daily necessities such
as edible oil, grains, vegetables and paper.
</P>
<P>
Such measures will reduce service costs and also enable faculty
members to concentrate more fully on teaching, and thus improve
the country's educational level, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
The city also plans to build dormitories covering an area of
one million sq.m outside the university campuses to solve student
housing problems, and to open chain stores at schools. University
clinics and kindergartens will also be changed into independent
organizations, offering service to both the schools and the
communities.
</P>
<P>
The reform process is to be completed by 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
