<HEADLINE> Int'l Arts Festival Closed in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The month-long First Shanghai
International Arts Festival, which included 136 artistic
performances, a six-day art expo, the Asian Music Festival, an
African art exhibition and a performing arts trade fair, closed
here today after a successful run.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding artists and performers from 24 countries including
the United States, Germany, France, and some Asian and African
countries presented programs and artwork in the festival.
</P>
<P>
More than 240,000 people attended 52 separate performances.
Tickets for some famous works such as Swan Lake, performed by a
Russian ballet troupe, were sold out.
</P>
<P>
Most of the plays in the festival were all well-known classical
works with special national characteristics. The participation of
some world-class arts groups, including the BBC's Welsh Orchestra
and the prestigious Royal Opera Company from the UK, along with
the French National Orchestra and the Franz Harary magic team from
the United States, also contributed to the success of the festival.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jiazheng, Minister of Culture and chairman of the festival'
s organizing committee, said at the closing ceremony that the
festival has achieved obvious social and economic benefits and it
will be a successful example for the further development of China'
s cultural industry and the cultural exchanges between China and
other countries.
</P>
<P>
Gong Xueping, deputy secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Party
Committee and deputy executive director of the festival, said that
the success of the fair provided experience for the future annual
arts festival.  
</P>
</TEXT>
