<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Leaves for Africa to Discuss U.S., U.N. Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. permanent
representative to the United Nations, Richard Holbrooke, Wednesday
heads for Africa on a tour to review the U.S. and U.N. role in a
continent riven by civil strife and stalked by AIDS, the No.1
killing disease in the world.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, who became the head of the U.S. Mission to the U.N.
in early September, is due to arrive in the West African country
of Mali on Wednesday before moving on to Angola on Thursday,
Namibia on Friday and South Africa on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The main themes of the tour would be relations with the U.N.
and the United States, peace in Congo (K), the scourge of HIV and
AIDS and environmental protection, a spokesman for the U.S.
Mission here said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is also due to meet U.N. representative in Angola, a
country rich in oil and diamonds where fighting has flared again
last December between Angolan Government troops and rebel National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), which has been
fighting for 25 years shortly after Angola's independence.
</P>
<P>
The envoy is expected to express U.S. support for a resolution
on ongoing civil strife in the former Zaire, and will visit most
of the countries involved in the war in Congo (K), where a many-
sided ceasefire is threatened.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke will also visit Rwanda and Uganda, which support
rebels of Congo (K), as well as Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe which
back Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution on Tuesday night,
asking U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to prepare equipment for
500 observers in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is scheduled to end his tour in Tunisia on December
11-12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
