<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intermediary Agencies to be Rectified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- China will sort out and rectify
its intermediary agencies in an attempt to give full play to their
role in maintaining market and economic order.
</P>
<P>
According to a circular issued by the General Office of the
State Council here today, the scope of the current rectification
covers all intermediary agencies and their trade organizations,
including accounting firms, financial consulting companies,
taxation and law offices, assets and price evaluation firms, and
project cost auditing organs.
</P>
<P>
The work will be done in three stages. First, all intermediary
agencies will be sorted out. Second, agencies to be retained will
separate their operations from government administration. Third,
management of intermediary agencies will be standardized and
unified.
</P>
<P>
A leading group composed of 10 government departments including
the Ministry of Finance, State Development Planning Commission and
Ministry of Supervision has been set up to oversee the
rectification work which will run through late 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to incomplete statistics, China had 20,000 economic
intermediary agencies with 160,000 professionals and 300,000 staff
members by the end of 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
