<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Opposed To New Round Of WTO Talks: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee said Wednesday that New Delhi did not favor a
wide-ranging new round of negotiations within the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee told parliament that India was also opposed to the
linkage of seven issues including labor and environment with
trade.
</P>
<P>
However, he said in a statement in response to questions raised
by the opposition that India was prepared for a few new items
being taken up for negotiations provided implementation issues
arising from the Uruguay Round were also resolved to its
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
On a reported deal between New Delhi and Washington at the
ongoing WTO ministerial meeting at Seattle, he said India was also
opposed to linking trade with core labor standards, environmental
issues, Coherent Global Architecture, investment issues,
non-governmental organizations' involvement in WTO negotiations
and competition policy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, some opposition members staged a noisy
walk-out after kicking up a row alleging that India and the U.S.
had entered into a "clandestine deal at Seattle" and demanded a
statement from Vajpayee to clarify the government's position on
the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
